commit_message:
fixup_stuff.sh plays nicely with old versions of prettytable

The fix for rights is applied only if the right version of
prettytable is installed on the system.

fixes bug #1236941

Change-Id: I9fe3d772bca3f781074d5dfff1ce096f3914474b

commit_message:
Support several output formats in state_graph tool

This commit adds -T aka --format option to state graph tool that
can be used to specify output format. Supported values are 'dot',
'svg', 'svgz' and 'png'.

Change-Id: I27a74b582726da24a1b05d4ffb72bde860fff417

commit_message:
Add a random uuid generator to data_utils

In some test cases, there are same code for using a random uuid string.
This commit introduces a random uuid generator(rand_uuid_str()) to
data_utils and changes for using the generator.

Change-Id: I4c4a2c993a9cedde3f8fa0f1a31b13d1eb4ed5e6

commit_message:
Replace unsuitable assertEqual with assertTrue/assertFalse

Since there are already two methods assertTrue/assertFalse for unit
test, we should use the more suitable method instead of
assertEqual(True/False,).

NOTE: this patch leaves assertEqual(0, len(arr)) untouched because
it is another style and can be modified to assertFalse(len(arr)) in a
different patch. Personally, i think it is more precise than
assertFalse.

Change-Id: I31c8b599f4632c05893e700848b8bd48c460d735
Closes-Bug: #1237425

'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-10-12 05:52:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Now I see three situation:
 - You have an already installed prettytable which does not have this issue (probably it is a distro package).

 - If your already installed version is in the expected range prettytable>=0.6,<0.8 , but not 0.7.2 the
 the original code fails without a real reason.
 
 - If your already installed version is out of range (prettytable>=0.6,<0.8) probably you will see an issue.
This situation is not covered by this change, and it was an issue before this change as well.
A possible solution is enforcing the version range here, but it will not be in sync with global requirements in the future.

- pip by default installing the latest 0.7.2 package if you do not have an already installed one, or your already had 0.7.2. In this case both the old and new code working properly. 

The real question is what will happen when the 0.7.x (x>2) released.
If >=0.7.2 will have the same issue, it will cause gate failure, as with the original code.

Our options are:
 - Enforcing the installation of v0.7.2:
    - We will upgrade(or downgrade) package from the accepted range. It is not a necessary operation. We might not update to new version when it is possible.
 - Touch more files permission (every version) even if it is not required.
    (Probably it was not an issue with the older versions.)
 - We are risking a gate issue if the new version will have the same issue. (This was the situation before and after this change.)
This option expects, prettytable will be fixed in the newer version.

Would you like to change the original strategy ? 
Which one do you prefer  ?'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-14 15:29:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

As you say, if the hypothetical prettytable 0.7.3 has this problem then the gate breaks.  This is intentional as we need to know if that is the case. [see below for more on that.]  This script is meant to address short-term fixes for upstream brokenness.  It performs the package installs so we can fix their brokenness before pip starts resolving the dependencies on our code.  It does assume that we're going to ignore (or overwrite if you're on CentOS) a system package that may be present is true, but pip would do that later anyway if the system package does not meet requirements.txt

The good thing about the permissions fixes is that Donald cleaned this up for us in pip 1.4.2 so once we can assume that pip 1.4 is not being used we can remove them.  And once we know the gate has >= 1.4.2 we can forget about worrying about a broken prettytable 0.7.3 or whatever there.

The py26 stuff does need to be handled, thanks."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-16 17:55:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

There have been a number of attempts to fix this problem, none quite right.  I have submitted https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52176/ as a fix.  Please have a look and see if it addresses your issue."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-10-17 06:01:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

thx'}]

commit_message:
fixup_stuff python 2.6 and prettytable fix

Since the 'set -o errexit' added the devstack install fails with python
2.6 even if the egg permission fixup is not required.

If the python version is reported using the usually py 2.6 directories
for SITE_DIRS.

'pip_install prettytable' does not upgrades the prettytable to the
latest 0.7.2 version if the system has an already installed
prettytable.

Most packages requires prettytable>=0.6,<0.8 so the forced upgrade to
0.7.2 is not required.
Changing the condition to only attempt to change the permission,
 when the 0.7.2 files are exists.

Change-Id: Iadab72e926848716085a0ce24cdd43753e9ed396

commit_message:
Fix fixup_stuff.sh package permissions fix

There are a number of different attempts to fix this issue, specifcally on RHEL6.
None of them actually get it right.
* This does not upgrade an OS installed package because we trust them to not make
  these sorts of permissions mistakes. Also we do not have nor want to figure out the
  right version that the OpenStack projects will require.
* This specfically targets the upstream package versions as we do not know how
  later versions behave.

This should address the following reviews:
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/50540/
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51233/ (1238707)
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51651/ (1239747)
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51843/
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51838/
* https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52148/ (1236941)

Change-Id: I99906451dc25654628187b383e8893cce0e276bf

commit_message:
Remove task_action state checks

Move to using the states module and its
set of states we can ignore transitions to
accomplish the same effect that our previous
task_action lists were accomplishing.

Change-Id: I06c785c0c543634c033997cab22a1f5409f41f25

commit_message:
Fixes to the compute node to enable SSH to VMs

* Some nova.conf changes - vncserver_listen=0.0.0.0, public_interface=eth0
* Some api-paste.ini additions - auth_port = 35357, auth_protocol = http
* No canonical callout on guestfs, launchpad doesn't show it as their call
* Adds security groups so you can ssh into launched instances
* Whitespace fixes

Closes-bug: 1240443

Change-Id: Ib9b2112aa54a207d17e613506233343e5ebd95b9

commit_message:
python3: iteration order of dict is unpredictable

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ
across Python runs.

Sort the metadata.keys() in reverse order to keep the test cases as is.

Change-Id: I233ada4dae4e9c0bc97bf8fd7d912a0eff9dd5b8
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Release candidate for docs for Havana

* Replaces master with havana in book files for labeling purposes;
we could just do this for the install and config guides though, so
please review and comment
* Ensures pom.xml files all use 1.11.1
* Adds release history info to each book
* Removes folsom/index.html
* Puts 2013.2 (havana version) and 1.10.1 (swift version) where needed
* Adds link to Havana release notes in wiki

Change-Id: I186f409bb5e8bf8538ca9ff599b29b2e133f9a04

commit_message:
Replace mox with mox3

Mox3 is an unofficial port of the Google mox framework
(http://code.google.com/p/pymox/) to Python 3.
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/mox3

Align with global-requirement and update the importing clause.

There is still py33 issue induced by keystoneclient.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51788/

When keystoneclient is upgraded in requirements.txt, all py33
issues should be fixed.

Change-Id: If0d00c088779b4a71e606cc87b37b5b1f9701081
Implement: blueprint py33-support

commit_message:
powervm tests: replace assertEquals with assertEqual

In Python 2.6, both assertEqual and assertEquals are
convenience aliases to failUnlessEqual.

In Python 3, failUnlessEqual is explicitly deprecated.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I978f61e5340ea554ec81118d8d282d10e28fe00d

commit_message:
Revert "Removes unnecessary api-paste.ini configuration"

This change should have never been merged b/c it appears to not
work for upgrades b/c of the precedence for configuration
lookups. It needs to be submitted together with code to remove
the previous configuration elements.

This reverts commit 3cf9a45458672862ce4e81a3ce45cd98112f93d4

commit_message:
python3: Refactor dict for python2/python3 compat

Python3 changed the behavior of dict.keys such that it is now
returns a dict_keys object, which is iterable but not indexable.
You can get the python2 result back with an explicit call to list.

Change-Id: Ic504d3929398aa82ac87d1735cf4cedea2dfc5d1

commit_message:
Use nose skip exception conditionally

testtools and nose disagree on the exception raised for skipping
tests with python < 2.7 (see inline comments for exact details).

This monkey-patches testtools to recognise the nose skip exception.
However, due to nose being deprecated we hide this behind an
environment variable to make it an opt-in fix.

While we're there, modify tempest.test.api.utils @skip_unless_attr
decorator to raise from tempest's BaseTestCase rather than
testtools.TestCase directly.

Conflicts:
	tempest/test.py

Change-Id: I13a8f374e879799870bc9193a1ddbdc8d6abb73c
(cherry picked from commit 98c35f3b430e2b364c1650c08154ce969626af38)

commit_message:
Remove duplicated test cases

The class ServersControllerCreateTest has the following duplicated
test cases since I091f14a9753059d759ba2f7b05ff33f5abea0f00 :

 * test_create_instance_with_config_drive_disabled
 * test_create_instance_local_href
 * test_create_instance_admin_pass_empty
 * test_create_instance_invalid_personality
 * test_create_location

This patch removes the duplicated test cases.
In addition, this removes the bookhref of test_create_location() also,
because it is not used.

Change-Id: I218d5ff443d4dbcec7520eab0b42e77fbd30eba8

commit_message:
Fixes broken doc references

The references in configuringservices.rst did not resolve to
html addresses and were not referenced correctly in the browser.
This new fix will use the preferred way to cross reference documents.
Has the disadvantage that if the reference changes, it need to be
updated at severeal places in the document.

Change-Id: I3b8f71a95e66266b569aa1141985e47f1f4554c3
Closes-Bug: 1232878

commit_message:
Sync jsonutils from oslo

Synce the changes of jsonutils from oslo, following fixes are synced:

Ia915f3175bee370d747e362cd9d35d8536c1b7b2
Id1aa7af26b0f5d929337cc373c6a4f802bba2cec
Ic94f238a5f92f28ae1b6154fb56f00c4c9fa3283
I8b246f20f9001379fcb5ca3a84aabee3847cb945

Most of them are py33 fixes, and keystoneclient is required by a dozen of
projects, we should update it to avoid py33 issue in dependent projects.

Closes-Bug #1239602

Change-Id: I65c28896d1551fd537dd7774e87bc479a477a7ab

commit_message:
Adds more uniformity to identity update_user calls

 * It was not possible to change a user's name using the KVS driver.
 * The KVS driver was not filtering the user dict before handing it
   back to that caller.
 * Adds a test to the LDAP driver to explicitly show that changing a
   user's name is not allowed.

Related-Bug: #1214686
Change-Id: Ia0951a58ef09833849d3eb5e714c7efbd901f5c5

commit_message:
Replace mox with mox3

Mox3 is an unofficial port of the Google mox framework
(http://code.google.com/p/pymox/) to Python 3.
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/mox3

Align with global-requirement and update the importing clause.

Partial implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: I3ce1748356c43b65ef81abefe67f777e915ba8e7

[{'created': '2013-10-16 08:17:02.000000000', 'message': 'Storwize: Fix iogrp availability check

Do not check if vdisk_count is greater than zero to determine iogrp
availability. This is wrong, and leads to the driver not being able to
use empty iogrps.

Change-Id: Ia73189a11cfcc0641c1527293675361c4e78443f
Closes-Bug: #1240395
'}]
commit_message:
Storwize: Fix iogrp availability check

Do not check if vdisk_count is greater than zero to determine iogrp
availability. This is wrong, and leads to the driver not being able to
use empty iogrps.

Change-Id: Ia73189a11cfcc0641c1527293675361c4e78443f
Closes-Bug: #1240395

commit_message:
Fix to use proper random values

In several tests, they need int values but use rand_name().
Especially, test_security_group_rules.py has a potentially bug.
And, when we will change the rand_name() to return string value, the
errors will occur in others.
So this commit fixes it and belows:
 * just import the module instead of importing the function
 * minor comment typo

Change-Id: Ic957c741b9ad3631d726dc6cfb5ecb9e0077a884

commit_message:
Improve display of instance image information

When instance is booted from volume image it returns a string,
while for instance from image returns a dict. Fix is made to
handle both cases.

Change-Id: I23aeccd21f88a353222d3fc7dc4b5c337c2bfecb
Closes-Bug: #1239896

scripts at multiple points in stack.sh.  This allows these scripts to
perform installation and startup tasks at similar times as they would
if integrated into stack.sh.

extras.d/70-tempest.sh is present as an example of the structure

'}]
commit_message:
Add stack phases to extras.d handling

Add hooks to stack.sh, unstack.sh and clean.sh to call the extras.d
scripts at multiple points in stack.sh.  This allows these scripts to
perform installation and startup tasks at similar times as they would
if integrated into stack.sh.

extras.d/70-tempest.sh is present as an example of the structure
of these scripts.

See extras.d/README.md for more information.

Change-Id: Ic1fe522559b94d204d6c0319a2e3d23684c8d028

commit_message:
Removes unwanted mox and fixture files

Module ironic.openstack.commom.fixture.moxstubout and mockptch
are no longer needed, so the whole directory is removed by this
patch. mox is removed from test-requirements.txt because it is
no longer used in ironic unit test cases.

commit_message:
Add neutron parallel job

This commit creates a new neutron tox job that runs the same tests as
a non-neutron tempest job except for those that don't currently work
with neutron enabled. This will be used for debugging neutron in
parallel since smoke doesn't actually run much.

Change-Id: Ie8388af63c4701492523c16aa991045c470b0e9f

commit_message:
Revert patch causing Instance Image Perf Issue

The previous patch https://review.openstack.org/52115 is causing
image get call for each instance. Reverting this back.

Fix will follow in another patch.

Related to bug: Bug: #1239896

Change-Id: If0d6feba50eb3f45248019fcc48580d1eae60d67

commit_message:
Remove general assumption in get_packages()

get_packages() always included 'general' as a default 'service' file.
Remove this assumption and add it explicitly to the primary package
installation call.  This allows get_package() to be used in other places
where 'general' is not desired to be included.

Change-Id: I1eed4386d073d6ae9534aedae32654208c6662e8

commit_message:
xenapi: stop agent errors stopping build

We should still report agent errors, but they should not stop a server
from building, because that server still may be ready to use.

Once this change is in place, we can look to selectively add back in
certain errors that fail the build, as we decide what makes sense on a
case by case basis.

Fixes bug 1233548
Change-Id: I32b9e8dbc6e28a045ac8ef159afe1cf74b7ac6fb

commit_message:
A nicer calling convention for object instantiation

This patch makes the base object constructor take some arguments
to streamline the process of creating a new object. By taking
a context and an optional set of keyword args, we can reduce
the lines of code required to create an object from many to, often,
one.

Change-Id: Id85c70d04af500ece48e9c93ee55a8e3d579299d

Note to self: looks like this wasn't caught in the existing pci_manager unit tests because the pci_request.get_instance_pci_requests method is stubbed out to always return a fake pci_request value.  From looking at the code, the only way that the internal claims dict can be mapped to None is when get_instance_pci_requests doesn't return anything, so that must be what's happening here. commit_message:
Check for None when cleaning PCI dev usage

The PCI manager needs to check for instance UUIDs mapped to
None when cleaning up it's internal claims/allocations maps.

Also adds a check so the claims dict doesn't map to None in
the first place.  There was already a check like this when
setting a value in the allocations dict.

Closes-Bug: #1238374

Change-Id: I7ac010f7d50ad85c145e536cfd48e07c8f4602d3

Yes, you can end up with some instances 'stuck' in the 'deleting' task state while a cell is down.  But you certainly shouldn't have a cell down for very long.  That'd be bad, as you mention.

This is better behavior than deleting immediately where you think you deleted your instance, but you really haven't.  Ie, things are more in sync this way. A regression was introduced with object conversion that caused all
instances to be locally deleted in the API cell when cells is enabled.
This would happen before the child cell was told to delete the instance.

Fixes bug 1240247

Change-Id: I94cfddd9cef2d63b2cb31c0f2dae8e211a4418d9
'}, {'created': '2013-10-16 04:10:08.000000000', 'message': "Cells: Fix instance deletes

A regression was introduced with object conversion that caused all
instances to be locally deleted in the API cell when cells is enabled.
This would happen before the child cell was told to delete the instance.

Additionally, if an instance record was created in a child cell but
failed to schedule to a host in such a way that the API cell has
no knowledge of the 'host', the instance would be deleted in the API
cell only.

Also, it appears that we would cast deletes to child cells twice due to
logic duplicated in cells_api.py that exists in api.py.

Closes-Bug: #1240247

Change-Id: I94cfddd9cef2d63b2cb31c0f2dae8e211a4418d9
"}]
commit_message:
Cells: Fix instance deletes

A regression was introduced with object conversion that caused all
instances to be locally deleted in the API cell when cells is enabled.
This would happen before the child cell was told to delete the instance.

Additionally, if an instance record was created in a child cell but
failed to schedule to a host in such a way that the API cell has
no knowledge of the 'host', the instance would be deleted in the API
cell only.

Also, it appears that we would cast deletes to child cells twice due to
logic duplicated in cells_api.py that exists in api.py.

Closes-Bug: #1240247

Change-Id: I94cfddd9cef2d63b2cb31c0f2dae8e211a4418d9

commit_message:
Add CIDR field type

This field type provides a strong verification that a value
assigned to a CIDR field is valid. This will be used for
the SecurityGroupRuleObject to follow.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: Ib62a515eea563da3107a3aed516a51d0ff55ba35

This option was deprecated in Havana and can now be removed.  Its only
use was for changing out the API class if cells was in use.
Technically, it used to be possible to configure an arbitrary compute
API class.  However, that would have been an unsupported setup, and has
been completely broken since 9f902c7e17249cf5af1504f31d80c0247a02fe20
anyway.

As a part of this change, the cell_type configuration option needed a
default value.  I set it to 'compute'.  My reasoning was that you would

more common case.

Change-Id: I5ec44f84267a700da16b350e686eee886e0d1183
"}]
commit_message:
Remove compute_api_class config option

This option was deprecated in Havana and can now be removed.  Its only
use was for changing out the API class if cells was in use.
Technically, it used to be possible to configure an arbitrary compute
API class.  However, that would have been an unsupported setup, and has
been completely broken since 9f902c7e17249cf5af1504f31d80c0247a02fe20
anyway.

As a part of this change, the cell_type configuration option needed a
default value.  I set it to 'compute'.  My reasoning was that you would
have more compute cells than API cells, so might as well set it to the
more common case.

Change-Id: I5ec44f84267a700da16b350e686eee886e0d1183

Flattened chapter structure.

Added basic Manage Services chapter, and placed Identity and Compute sections inside. Redid Compute section header to match. Removed installation instructions (user should already have installed).

commit_message:
Remove aggregate metadata methods from conductor and virtapi

The aggregate_metadata_add() and aggregate_metadata_remove()
methods are no longer needed in virtapi and conductor. This
patch removes them from the former and deprecates them in the
latter. Also, aggregate_get_by_host() is no longer needed in
virtapi, so remove it from there.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: Ia057dcc43c555187a4a1466a9e748b978c46d4a4

What's going on? Why is that approach not workable?"}, {'account_id': 518, 'date': '2013-10-16 19:11:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

As I explained in the commit message for the existing fix, there is no "correct" order in which to reset TestCase.stubs and TestCase.mox.stubs.

If you reset TestCase.mox.stubs first, but you overrode the method last in TestCase.stubs, you're going to hit this bug, and vice versa.

The correct fix is to share the stubs attribute and fix the test cases that are resetting the stubs halfway through and still expecting them to be in place.'}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-10-16 20:11:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Soren:

Order shouldn't matter, however, in practice it does, so the convention has been to stub-before-mocking because we unmock-before-unstubbing.

That has worked fine up until the point Olso switched the cleanup order back to the original, broken way.

I agree that sharing stubs would be a very elegant solution (I vaguely think I looked into doing this in the original Nova patch).

I recall there being issues with it, and the failing tests in Nova indicate that it isn't a drop-in replacement approach.

I think it has to do with the fact that if they share a cache of original-functions, then the last-one to write wins, causing the first stubbed out function not to be reverted. I'd need to double-check the mox code to make sure this is really the case.

But either way, at the very least, this patch allows all the tests to pass.

I'd argue that we should merge this immediately since it's causing major headaches for Nova devs, and then debate the best approach offline."}, {'account_id': 518, 'date': '2013-10-16 20:26:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I have a fix for the failing tests. I'll submit in a few minutes."}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-10-16 20:47:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Looks like Soren got the Nova tests passing with the shared-stubs approach.

Looked back through the stubout/mox code and didn't see anything that looked like the shared-stubs approach is inherently bad.

So, abandoning this patch in favor of just using that.

Thanks for fixing this the right way, Soren!"}]

commit_message:
Fix cleanup ordering in moxstubout fixture

The ordering of fixture cleanup calls is very important in preventing test
interactions.

Originally, Nova got this ordering wrong, so we had to fix it here:

   4e560d49d4a8d08341dae6df5e123e1be1b3c779

Unfortunately, when the fixture was added to Oslo, it was added using the
original, incorrect ordering.

This caused Nova to regress and suffer the same sporadic test failures we had
when fixing the original Nova bug.

A recent commit (f4a485530ebd123cdb80b8b8a378ff9847b2a5d7) attempted to fix
this by sharing stubs between the self.stubs and self.mox.

Unfortunately, this caused other Nova tests to fail
(nova/tests/network/test_manager.py).

The fix is to use the original Nova fixture with the correct cleanup ordering.

Fixes bug 1239898

Change-Id: I0971eacf165667bb060b5cd7ec4f8182d71346e1

commit_message:
V2 RpcApi should register when db pool is enabled

The rpc api controller registers the public methods of db_api
But, use_tpool is True, the thread pool wrapper's methods are
used which would lead to failures.

Fixes Bug #1221037

Change-Id: Iaba10178c7da1548257e2180658c2dc8ba3e048b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-15 18:43:07.000000000', 'message': "Add storage policy support for the Replicator

Replicator support for Storage Policies

Adds storoge policy awareness to the replicator service so that it
processes all policy rings according to their type.  Thus it also
extends storage policies to include a 'type' element per policy.
The 'type' will default to 'replication' if not specified.  Below
it is specified for example purposes:

[storage-policy:0]
name = chicken
type = replication

Change-Id: I44a103b8a475408b221062050c1ea652bca64702
Implements: swift-ec
"}]
commit_message:
Add storage policy support for the Replicator

Replicator support for Storage Policies

Adds storoge policy awareness to the replicator service so that it
processes all policy rings according to their type.  Thus it also
extends storage policies to include a 'type' element per policy.
The 'type' will default to 'replication' if not specified.  Below
it is specified for example purposes:

[storage-policy:0]
name = chicken
type = replication

Change-Id: I44a103b8a475408b221062050c1ea652bca64702
Implements: swift-ec

commit_message:
Replace OpenStack LLC with OpenStack Foundation

Some files still use trademark OpenStack LLC in header, which
should be changed to OpenStack Foundation.

NOTE: tools/install_venv.py is not touched, should sync with oslo

Change-Id: I01d4f6b64cf1a152c4e190407799ce7d53de845f
Fixes-Bug: #1214176

commit_message:
Enable tasks data model and table for async worker

Add tasks data model and table for async worker to
store the tasks data persistently.

Partially implement blueprint async-glance-workers

Change-Id: I2b2d70295da4905bf75cffc2b2eadec174d1abfc

Not sure how to affect the swift.conf file used by Jenkins but will jump on IRC tomorrow if I don't see it somewhere pretty obvious"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-08-02 18:00:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

You should fix the code so it falls back to the default behavior if the new section is present ;)

Also you should have an example of the new section in etc/proxy-server.conf ;)

I need to look at this in much more detail - thanks for putting it out there."}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-08-02 19:01:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Clay - wasn't sure how paranoid to be wrt making sure the cluster admin/installer knew what they were doing wrt ring setup so I figured I'd make it fail if someone didn't specify what policies they wanted to define.  Key point there is define - if an admin defined a policy but fails to specify one for a particular container then it will indeed use the default its just the way it is now, default must be defined in swift.conf as triple replication. Let me know if that changes your mind but either way I'll do as you suggest so I can see if Jenkins will pass that way (or if something else comes back).  Appreciate you taking a look at it and welcome any/all feedback and advice"}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-08-02 20:58:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-08-02 21:01:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 21:52:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

Note that on the Application class and test code interface:  previously either object_ring (the parm) was None or it was a ring passed by the test code (FakeRing).  Now it can be one of three values:

none:  same meaning as before
object_rings (list of rings):  when there is just one ring on this list, it has the same meaning as the repvious usage where a single ring was passed
object_rings (list of rings):  when there is > 1 ring on the list passed in, it is also the test code instantiating the class whoever the Application class is mean to instantiate the rings passed in.  This is the same case as before where the test code would instantiate the Application class w/o an object-ring parm and this third case is needed to support unit test code that wants to test > 1 ring'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-07 19:11:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I haven't really gone too in-depth here, but I have a couple of early thoughts.

First: I don't think we should have ring_name in the config; I think that should be implicitly defined by the name of the policy. That is, if you have "[storage-policy:alpaca]" in your config, the filename of the ring shall be object-alpaca.ring.gz. That way operators don't have to deal with setting up some mapping. (If you want two policies using the same ring, make a symlink.)

That would also let you throw out a bunch of code for validating storage policies, which is always nice.

Second: It's a little odd that a swob.Request might have a ring associated with it. A Request represents an HTTP request from a client; tacking a ring on there seems a little out-of-place. Not the end of the world, and like I said, I haven't really gone in-depth here, but it strikes me as weird.

Third, and this is really minor: let's not call the policy "triple-repl", as one could, in principle, have a 2-replica policy or a 10-replica policy, so the 'triple' is a bit of a misnomer.

Fourth: X-Container-Meta-Storage-Policy should be settable only on initial container creation, as containers without one will implicitly have the default policy. And we should probably call it just X-Storage-Policy (maybe?), as it's not just your normal container metadata. There's a setting to let arbitrary headers get stored that don't start with X-Container-Meta; use that. This way we don't have to worry about users that have already set X-Storage-Policy, as they won't have been able to before. If we use X-Container-Meta-Storage-Policy, there's a (small) chance that existing containers will have that attribute set, and that'll goof things up pretty effectively.

I'll take a deeper look later today and provide any additional feedback I come up with.'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-08-07 19:50:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Work In Progress

I think there's still some confusion here about how these policies map to how things are stored. Let me lay out what I'm thinking as best I can, and hopefully that'll help clear things up.

In my head, a storage policy has three attributes: a name, a storage method, and an associated ring. Now, certain storage methods (I'm looking at you, erasure codes) may need extra attributes to define more things, but the basic, minimal storage policy only needs name, storage-method, and ring.

When it comes to specifying these attributes, we can whittle down the required configuration even further. The name is mandatory; Swift has no way of creating that. The ring's name can be built from the policy's name, so we can leave that implicit. Also, the storage method can default to replicated, so we don't even need to specify that.

So, let's have a three-policy system: the default policy ("default") will be the usual 3 replicas; the super-expensive policy ("diamond") will have 5 replicas, and the really cheap policy ("radium") will have just 1 (and much like radium-228, these objects will have a half-life of only a few years).

The config file:

    [storage-policy:diamond]
    # storage method is implicitly replicated
    
    [storage-policy:radium]
    # storage method is implicitly replicated

    # there's also an implicit [storage-policy:default] in here

Notice that there's no mention of the number of replicas in the config file. That's because the number of replicas is controlled by the ring files on disk. If diamond policy is to have 5 replicas, then /etc/swift/object-diamond.ring.gz will be set to have 5 replicas. Similarly, /etc/swift/object-radium.ring.gz will have just 1 replica defined.

This gives cluster operators more flexibility later. Should it turn out that diamond tier only really needs 4 replicas instead of 5, the operator can then alter the ring without having to also update a config file. Also, by specifying number-of-replicas in only one place, we can avoid writing code to handle mismatches between config files and rings.

This also lets cluster operators have multiple policies with the same replica count. Using something like [storage-policy:triple-repl] doesn't allow for multiple 3-replica policies. For example, a cluster operator may want to offer standard 3-replica storage on spinning disks at $X/GB, but also offer fast 3-replica storage on SSDs for $5X/GB. Keying things off an opaque name keeps this possible.

This works well for users too, as they can specify "X-Storage-Tier: diamond" in their container PUT request and then  not worry about what, exactly, "diamond" storage is. Keeps the interface simple.'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-08-12 20:42:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Work In Progress

'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-04 16:54:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 33: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(9 inline comments)

First, sorry for letting this languish. I've been sick the last week or so, and both the cold and the cold medicine made it hard to think clearly.

Okay, so, the code:

I feel like doing the name-to-index translation inside of check_metadata() is a bit weird. Nothing else in check_metadata() is mutating the request; it's all read-only validation. Also, this would let a client specify X-Storage-Policy-Index (by omitting X-Storage-Policy), and the proxy should not let that through to the backend. I can't see any good coming of it, but I do foresee opportunities for malice.

I noted this in an inline comment too, but in the object server, DATADIR can't be an instance variable since it's shared between greenlets.

Also, a minor nit: the use of triple-quotes for comments is generally considered poor style in Python. They'll definitely get flagged by other devs when this is submitted to master, so you should probably convert them to normal comments.

There's also a bunch of minutiae called out in various inline comments; that's about the level of review I was capable of earlier in the week. :)"}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2013-10-04 23:19:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 33: Work In Progress

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-01 23:31:17.000000000', 'message': 'Add general multi-ring support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a list of object rings.  The list includes not only the Ring object itself
but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and any other meta
data associated with the policy that may be needed.

The list of object rings is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time.  The format of the sections in the .conf file is self-
explanatory and a list is exported from utils.py that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated when Application() is instantiated
and then Application.object.nodes is updated with the addresses.  There is a new
accessor method called Application.get_object_ring() that returns the Ring address
based on the policy passed in.  There is basic error handling in both the conf file
parser as well as the accessor function to assure the conf file is formed correctly
and that the defaulr triple-repl ring is returned as default.

This commit focuses only on the Proxy server (storage node services using the obj
rings will be next) and the unit test framework.  No new tests have been added yet
as the number of changes required to support multiple rings in the test framwork
was large.

Ring selection is done at public entry points based on container metadata.  If the
container has the metadata X-Container-Meta_Storage_Policy and there is a match
with the policy name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be
used.  If not then triple-repl will be the default.  The new container metadata
policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a conflict error
will be returned.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

The following highlights the major changes in thsi commit:

* objecr ring address stored in Request class to support different rings for
concurrent IOs (there is only one instance of the Application class)
* swift.conf file parser support for storage policies
* container update to support immutable storage policy metadata
* a few misc function parm changes to enable passing of ring info
* use of ring based on container metadata in objController public functions
* use of specific ring for internally generated requests
* Application class changes to support new element - a list of dict items
representing the supported storage policies and Ring addresses
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings

Change-Id: I53bcad1dc724596c5c4ec8a30d5cf50ebe7f1b7d
Implements:  blueprint ec-proxy-work

policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a conflict error
will be returned.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

representing the supported storage policies and Ring addresses
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings

'}, {'created': '2013-08-19 20:04:56.000000000', 'message': "Add general multi-ring support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a collection of object rings. The collection includes not only the Ring
object itself but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and
any other meta data associated with the policy that may be needed.

The policy collection is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time. The format of the sections in the .conf file is covered
below and accessed via get_storage_policies() that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated when Application() is instantiated
and then Application.object.nodes is updated with the addresses. There is a new
accessor method called Application.get_object_ring() that returns the Ring address
based on the policy passed in. There is basic error handling in both the conf file
parser as well as the accessor functions to assure the conf file is formed correctly.

swift.conf format:

	[storage-policy:0]
	name = chicken

	[storage-policy:1]
	name = turkey
	default = yes

	[storage-policy:2]
	name = gravy
	ec-scheme:14:10

With the above format:

- policy 0 will always be used for access to existing containers w/o the policy specified.
The ring name for polic 0 is always 'object' assuring backwards compatiblity.  The parser
will always create a policy 0 even if not specified
- the policy with 'default=yes' is the one used for new container creation and allows the
admin to specify which policy is used without forcing the application to add the metadata.
- use of 'ec-scheme' implies that the associated ring is built for erasure code and
includes the ec scheme parameter.  A policy w/o any other tag like this implies replication
using where the # of copies is determined by how the ring was built

This commit focuses only on the Proxy server (storage node services using the obj
rings will be next) and the unit test framework. No new tests have been added yet
as the number of changes required to support multiple rings in the test framwork
was large.

Ring selection is done at public entry points based on container metadata. If the
container has the metadata X-Container-Storage-Policy and there is a match
with the policy name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be
used. If not then decisions are made per description of swift.conf sectiosn above.

The container metadata policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a c
onflict error will be returned. An attempt to create a container with a policy not defined
results in a bad reqeust error.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

The following highlights the major changes in this commit:

* swift.conf file parser support for storage policies
* container update to support immutable storage policy metadata
* a few misc function parm changes to enable passing of ring info
* use of ring based on container metadata in objController public functions
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings

container has the metadata X-Container-Storage-Policy and there is a match
with the policy name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be
used. If not then decisions are made per description of swift.conf sectiosn above.

onflict error will be returned. An attempt to create a container with a policy not defined
results in a bad reqeust error.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it

"}, {'created': '2013-08-20 13:22:48.000000000', 'message': "Add general multi-ring support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a collection of object rings. The collection includes not only the Ring
object itself but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and
any other meta data associated with the policy that may be needed.

The policy collection is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time. The format of the sections in the .conf file is covered
below and accessed via get_storage_policies() that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated when Application() is instantiated
and then Application.object.nodes is updated with the addresses. There is a new
accessor method called Application.get_object_ring() that returns the Ring address
based on the policy passed in. There is basic error handling in both the conf file
parser as well as the accessor functions to assure the conf file is formed correctly.

swift.conf format:

	[storage-policy:0]
	name = chicken

	[storage-policy:1]
	name = turkey
	default = yes

	[storage-policy:2]
	name = gravy
	ec-scheme = 14:10

With the above format:

- policy 0 will always be used for access to existing containers w/o the policy specified.
The ring name for polic 0 is always 'object' assuring backwards compatiblity.  The parser
will always create a policy 0 even if not specified
- the policy with 'default=yes' is the one used for new container creation and allows the
admin to specify which policy is used without forcing the application to add the metadata.
- use of 'ec-scheme' implies that the associated ring is built for erasure code and
includes the ec scheme parameter.  A policy w/o any other tag like this implies replication
using where the # of copies is determined by how the ring was built

"}, {'created': '2013-09-14 22:14:06.000000000', 'message': "Add general multi-ring support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a collection of object rings. The collection includes not only the Ring
object itself but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and
any other meta data associated with the policy that may be needed.

The policy collection is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time. The format of the sections in the .conf file is covered
below and accessed via get_storage_policies() that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated when Application() is instantiated
and then Application.object.nodes is updated with the addresses. There is a new
accessor method called Application.get_object_ring() that returns the Ring address
based on the policy passed in. There is basic error handling in both the conf file
parser as well as the accessor functions to assure the conf file is formed correctly.

swift.conf format:

	[storage-policy:0]
	name = chicken

	[storage-policy:1]
	name = turkey
	default = yes

With the above format:

- policy 0 will always be used for access to existing containers w/o the policy specified.
The ring name for polic 0 is always 'object' assuring backwards compatiblity.  The parser
will always create a policy 0 even if not specified
- the policy with 'default=yes' is the one used for new container creation and allows the
admin to specify which policy is used without forcing the application to add the metadata.
- in the future new elements can be added such as 'ec-scheme' which would imply that the
associated ring is built for erasure code and includes some ec scheme parameters.
A policy w/o any other tag like this implies replication using where the # of copies is
determined by how the ring was built

This commit focuses only on the Proxy server (storage node services using the obj
rings will be next) and the unit test framework changes and new unit tests.

Ring selection is done at public entry points based on container metadata. If the
container has the metadata X-Storage-Policy and there is a match with the policy
name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be used. If not then
decisions are made per description of swift.conf sectiosn above.  Note that internally
there is a policy index that is used in conjunction with X-Storage-Policy that enables
the cluster admin to both support backwards compatibility as well as choose the
default that is most applicable for their cluster.  The internal metadata stored in
containers is called X-Storage-Policy-Index.

The container metadata policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a c
onflict error will be returned. An attempt to create a container with a policy not defined
results in a bad reqeust error.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

The following highlights the major changes in this commit:

* swift.conf file parser support for storage policies (new storage_policy.py)
* container update to support immutable storage policy metadata
* a few misc function parm changes to enable passing of ring info
* use of ring based on container metadata in objController public functions
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings
* unit tests covering all new functinality

Change-Id: I53bcad1dc724596c5c4ec8a30d5cf50ebe7f1b7d
Implements:  blueprint ec-proxy-work

'}, {'created': '2013-10-11 20:35:26.000000000', 'message': 'Add Storage Policy Support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a collection of object rings. The collection includes not only the Ring
object itself but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and
any other meta data associated with the policy that may be needed.  When containers
are created, a policy (thus a specific obj ring) is selected allowing apps to
specify policy at container creation time and leverage policies simply by using
different containers for object operations.

The policy collection is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time. The format of the sections in the .conf file is covered
below and accessed via get__policies() that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated "just in time" when the App
method get_object_ring() is inoked for the first time per policy. There is basic
error handling in both the conf file parser as well as the accessor functions to
assure the conf file is formed correctly.

swift.conf format:

	[storage-policy:0]
	name = chicken

	[storage-policy:1]
	name = turkey
	default = yes

With the above format:

- policy 0 will always be used for access to existing containers w/o the policy specified.
The ring name for polic 0 is always 'object' assuring backwards compatiblity.  The parser
will always create a policy 0 even if not specified
- the policy with 'default=yes' is the one used for new container creation and allows the
admin to specify which policy is used without forcing the application to add the metadata.
- in the future new elements can be added such as 'ec-scheme' which would imply that the
associated ring is built for erasure code and includes some ec scheme parameters.
A policy w/o any other tag like this implies replication using where the # of copies is
determined by how the ring was built

This commit focuses only on the Proxy server (storage node services using the obj
rings will be next) and the unit test framework changes and new unit tests.

Ring selection is done at public entry points based on container metadata. If the
container has the metadata X-Storage-Policy and there is a match with the policy
name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be used. If not then
decisions are made per description of swift.conf sections above.  Note that internally
there is a policy index that is used in conjunction with X-Storage-Policy that enables
the cluster admin to both support backwards compatibility as well as choose the
default that is most applicable for their cluster.  The internal metadata stored in
containers is called X-Storage-Policy-Index.

The container metadata policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a c
onflict error will be returned. An attempt to create a container with a policy not defined
results in a bad reqeust error.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

The following highlights the major changes in this commit:

* swift.conf file parser support for storage policies (new storage_policy.py)
* container update to support immutable storage policy metadata
* a few misc function parm changes to enable passing of ring info
* use of ring based on container metadata in objController public functions
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings
* unit tests covering all new functinality

Storage Node services to support Storage Polciies are not included here.

commit_message:
Add Storage Policy Support

The basic idea here is to replace the use of a single object ring in the Application
class with a collection of object rings. The collection includes not only the Ring
object itself but the policy name assocaited with it, the filename for the .gz and
any other meta data associated with the policy that may be needed.  When containers
are created, a policy (thus a specific obj ring) is selected allowing apps to
specify policy at container creation time and leverage policies simply by using
different containers for object operations.

The policy collection is based off of info in the swift.conf file parsed at wsgi
application init time. The format of the sections in the .conf file is covered
below and accessed via get__policies() that has all of the info except
for the Ring addresses; the rings are instantiated "just in time" when the App
method get_object_ring() is inoked for the first time per policy. There is basic
error handling in both the conf file parser as well as the accessor functions to
assure the conf file is formed correctly.

swift.conf format:

	[storage-policy:0]
	name = chicken

	[storage-policy:1]
	name = turkey
	default = yes

With the above format:

- policy 0 will always be used for access to existing containers w/o the policy specified.
The ring name for polic 0 is always 'object' assuring backwards compatiblity.  The parser
will always create a policy 0 even if not specified
- the policy with 'default=yes' is the one used for new container creation and allows the
admin to specify which policy is used without forcing the application to add the metadata.
- in the future new elements can be added such as 'ec-scheme' which would imply that the
associated ring is built for erasure code and includes some ec scheme parameters.
A policy w/o any other tag like this implies replication using where the # of copies is
determined by how the ring was built

This commit focuses only on the Proxy server (storage node services using the obj
rings will be next) and the unit test framework changes and new unit tests.

Ring selection is done at public entry points based on container metadata. If the
container has the metadata X-Storage-Policy and there is a match with the policy
name provided and one parsed from swift.conf, that ring will be used. If not then
decisions are made per description of swift.conf sections above.  Note that internally
there is a policy index that is used in conjunction with X-Storage-Policy that enables
the cluster admin to both support backwards compatibility as well as choose the
default that is most applicable for their cluster.  The internal metadata stored in
containers is called X-Storage-Policy-Index.

The container metadata policy cannot be changed, if an attempt is made to change it a c
onflict error will be returned. An attempt to create a container with a policy not defined
results in a bad reqeust error.  Migrating data from one policy to another means copying it
from one container to another manually.

The following highlights the major changes in this commit:

* swift.conf file parser support for storage policies (new storage_policy.py)
* container update to support immutable storage policy metadata
* a few misc function parm changes to enable passing of ring info
* use of ring based on container metadata in objController public functions
* large number of changes to unit test framework to support multiple rings
but no new capabilities specifically geared at testing multiple rings
* unit tests covering all new functinality

Storage Node services to support Storage Polciies are not included here.

Change-Id: I53bcad1dc724596c5c4ec8a30d5cf50ebe7f1b7d
Implements:  blueprint ec-proxy-work

commit_message:
xenapi: Speedup vm_util and vmops tests

* Uses NODBTestCase in more places

* Also, adds VMUtilsTestBase so that all new test cases in test_vm_utils will,
by default, not use the database.

Speed up observed from running:

nosetests nova/tests/virt/xenapi/test_vm_utils.py
          nova/tests/virt/xenapi/test_vmops.py

BEFORE: Ran 113 tests in 7.674s
AFTER: Ran 113 tests in 1.873s

Change-Id: Id05ecac90201fba27cbae7480d3119cacd92ec24

commit_message:
Fix IP recycling on exhausted pool

When recycling an IP, allocation pools are loaded with an inner
join with ip avaiblity ranges. However, if the pool is exhausted,
there will be no availability ranges and the query will return
no results because of the inner join. It will therefore be
impossible to reuse IP addresses once the pool has been exhausted.

This patch tries to reload allocation pools without joining on
IP avaiability ranges if the first query did not return any result.
Replacing an inner join with an outer join will not be possible
as postgresql backend does not support 'SELECT ... FOR UPDATE' with
outer joins (for more info see bug 1215350).

The patch also contains unit tests for verifying IP are recycled
correctly even when the pool is exhausted.

Bug 1240353

Change-Id: I87f274bd759cb47be77717f0760d3704f9f34ade
(cherry picked from commit 72af3cef2a476b7f1f7d109d1bd37cd50a6f560e)

commit_message:
use proxy mode on vxlan interface only when l2-population is activated

the proxy mode was set by default on every vxlan interfaces
which leads to inaccessibility between VM that are not hosted
on the same host in a vxlan network

Closes-Bug: #1237082

Change-Id: I34028ee0bdfdccda61c6a29f58759259da060b68
(cherry picked from commit 345f8e1fdc65e0cf23369488d4318c0755d6b65d)

commit_message:
'Persist' __getattr__ results

This patch adds a new decorator that helps creating 'cachable'
__getattr__ methods. The decorator sets the returned value as an
attribute of the instance.

The patch also decorates `Pipeline`'s __getattr__ method

Implements blueprint storage-pipeline

Change-Id: I6b052d536d5c6e6edaeec884b3c4a0e8703b1036

add a try/finally to ensure the LOG.debug is printed
properly. Currently the debug message is never executed

commit_message:
Fix Huawei HVS driver AttributeError

This patch checks the iSCSI port info and raises an exception
if it can not get the port info from the configuration.

Closes-bug: #1237185
Change-Id: I341ccbe77abd25421e5ee0b2d07ace3759fbccef

commit_message:
Orchestration autoscaling improve status polling

This change includes the following improvements to the
autoscaling test:
- On stack create status timeout, override the error status so
  that FAILED stacks fail fast
- Improve the error message in assertScale
- Delete the stack at the end of the scenario, and confirm the delete
  succeeded

Change-Id: Ia220e3a2b422472ac7c6d29f9a5a61bd7c4987c3

commit_message:
Remove driver validation on node update

As discussed in the meeting on 14 Oct 2013, remove driver validation
when driver_info is changed.

Change-Id: Icca14742740b99d27a36d4dd315bb49d570cdeb2
Closes-Bug: #1237650

Hi Gray,

If there are the duplicated names of shelved images, we can identify the server of each snapshot like the following:

 $ nova list

 | ID                                   | Name | Status | Task State | Power State | Networks         |
 +--------------------------------------+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
 | a72ea626-a08d-40b2-b2b9-0ab66dda6a56 | vm01 | ACTIVE | None       | Running     | private=10.0.0.2 |
 | ddbfbb28-7140-4555-a678-408f612bb2e4 | vm01 | ACTIVE | None       | Running     | private=10.0.0.3 |
 +--------------------------------------+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
 $
 $ nova shelve a72ea626-a08d-40b2-b2b9-0ab66dda6a56
 $ nova shelve ddbfbb28-7140-4555-a678-408f612bb2e4
 $
 $ nova image-list
 +--------------------------------------+---------------------------------+--------+--------------------------------------+
 | ID                                   | Name                            | Status | Server                               |
 +--------------------------------------+---------------------------------+--------+--------------------------------------+
 | 6a360e42-d4d4-46bf-a744-75c6e690f25b | cirros-0.3.1-x86_64-uec         | ACTIVE |                                      |
 | 352ad788-1cf1-4a1a-b1da-d5fc8d3775fa | cirros-0.3.1-x86_64-uec-kernel  | ACTIVE |                                      |
 | a43f4512-56fd-4673-8f6e-e4f31ca9d795 | cirros-0.3.1-x86_64-uec-ramdisk | ACTIVE |                                      |
 | 763bc44e-5532-451e-abf3-0f32a4935b95 | vm01-shelved                    | ACTIVE | ddbfbb28-7140-4555-a678-408f612bb2e4 |
 | edc09a1b-510c-4c62-976e-cb62abc7fc52 | vm01-shelved                    | ACTIVE | a72ea626-a08d-40b2-b2b9-0ab66dda6a56 |
 +--------------------------------------+---------------------------------+--------+--------------------------------------+
 $

[{'created': '2013-09-30 04:53:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the image name of a shelved server

The shelve feature powers a server off, and creates a snapshot of the
server. The snapshot image name is "instance-XXXXXXXXX-shelved" and it
doesn't contain a server name like the following:

  $ nova list
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | ID | Name | Status | Task State | Power State | Networks         |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | .. | vm01 | ACTIVE | None       | Running     | private=10.0.0.5 |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  $ nova shelve vm01
  $ nova image-list
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name                            | Status | Server |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | instance-00000004-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  $

This patch changes the name to "<server name>-shelved", so that user
can know what snapshot more easily:

  $ nova image-list
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name               | Status | Server |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | vm01-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  $

Note: "nova shelve" command is review in progress.
      (Ic2ad1bb537efb40a3155e9f3c7b63e09e82be7f1)

Fixes bug #1232991

commit_message:
Fix the image name of a shelved server

The shelve feature powers a server off, and creates a snapshot of the
server. The snapshot image name is "instance-XXXXXXXXX-shelved" and it
doesn't contain a server name like the following:

  $ nova list
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | ID | Name | Status | Task State | Power State | Networks         |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | .. | vm01 | ACTIVE | None       | Running     | private=10.0.0.5 |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  $ nova shelve vm01
  $ nova image-list
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name                            | Status | Server |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | instance-00000004-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  $

"instance-XXXXXXXXX" is OS-EXT-SRV-ATTR:instance_name, and a non-admin
cannot see it.

This patch changes the name to "<server name>-shelved", so that a non-
admin user can know the server name of a shelved image:

  $ nova image-list
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name               | Status | Server |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | vm01-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  $

Closes-Bug: 1232991

Change-Id: Idc73658e29cb77dfcc8b046535a36affc1831605

commit_message:
Disable lazy gettext

This change disables lazy gettext functionality in Keystone,
due to problems with character encoding and logging
detailed in bug 1225099.

It is part of a series of commits across all projects with
lazy gettext enabled.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

commit_message:
add some negative tests for tenant

making a separate test_tenant_negative.py,and move the exist negative
tests over to it,and add some negative tests for in it.

- test_update_non_existent_tenant
- test_tenant_update_by_unauthorized_user
- test_tenant_update_request_without_token

Change-Id: Id0d15d312c96a3f8a244d5e08414623e3c15013a

Update Cisco N1KV plugin to VSM REST api calls

Modify the existing REST calls from the plugin to VSM to update the
attributes and use UUIDs as index, instead of string names, for all
the resources.

Change-Id: Icb4950ea7c6f036e9a25ee79e3f5fe30d40f47de

commit_message:
Adds test_update_all_metadata_field_not_included negative test

Adds test_update_all_metadata_field_not_included negative test
which checks a BadRequest is returned when attempting to
set the server metadata and not include the metadata field

Collapses all of the negative tests into one testcase as they
should not have any side effects and it will slightly reduce
setup overhead.

Change-Id: Iab221d23e896fb22bbe351bb20c0378ebaa60add
Closes-Bug: 1131536

When recycling an IP, allocation pools are loaded with an inner
join with ip avaiblity ranges. However, if the pool is exhausted,
there will be no availability ranges and the query will return
no results because of the inner join. It will therefore be
impossible to reuse IP addresses once the pool has been exhausted.

correctly even when the pool is exhausted.

commit_message:
Fix IP recycling on exhausted pool

When recycling an IP, allocation pools are loaded with an inner
join with ip avaiblity ranges. However, if the pool is exhausted,
there will be no availability ranges and the query will return
no results because of the inner join. It will therefore be
impossible to reuse IP addresses once the pool has been exhausted.

This patch tries to reload allocation pools without joining on
IP avaiability ranges if the first query did not return any result.
Replacing an inner join with an outer join will not be possible
as postgresql backend does not support 'SELECT ... FOR UPDATE' with
outer joins (for more info see bug 1215350).

The patch also contains unit tests for verifying IP are recycled
correctly even when the pool is exhausted.

Bug 1240353

Change-Id: I87f274bd759cb47be77717f0760d3704f9f34ade

commit_message:
use proxy mode on vxlan interface only when l2-population is activated

the proxy mode was set by default on every vxlan interfaces
which leads to inaccessibility between VM that are not hosted
on the same host in a vxlan network

Closes-Bug: #1237082

Change-Id: I34028ee0bdfdccda61c6a29f58759259da060b68

Are you doing this from Thomas point of view?

There's the same kind of issues already with things like argparse, and this is handle by pbr without any problem. So what Thomas describes is a short sighted view of the problem IMHO. We can fix this if you want to use 'ordereddict'."}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-10-16 12:09:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Julien,

Thanks for your review.

I've mailed the glance dev list to see what the wider view on this is.

This is my change (I pinged Thomas to get a packager's viewpoint).

Any chance you'd be able to give a brief outline of how a pbr based fix would work? I'm not overly familiar with pbr; I'd like to understand for example how an 'import ordereddict' would work on a system that didn't have the python-ordereddict .deb package installed.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-10-16 12:26:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We have a list of requirements in pbr which should be excluded from actually being added to install_requires on >=2.7 (there are some things that are backport-packaged for 2.6, so we have to use them, but requiring them for 2.7 is wrong.) See:

https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-dev/pbr/tree/pbr/packaging.py#n52'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-10-16 12:27:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

What could be done is for pbr to be aware that if you run setup.py with Python >= 2.7, there's no need to "pip install ordereddict".

There's no magic solution for your code. So it will have deal with this until Python 2.6 support is dropped, but that's easy enough to just write:

try:
    from collections import OrderedDict
except ImportError:
    from ordereddict import OrderedDict


As from packaging side, just this would make sure they would not have to package ordereddict anyway.

So I really thing moving you are on the right way so far!'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-10-16 12:27:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-10-16 13:16:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Just spotted Monty's reply on the mailing list:

"Debian/Ubuntu are not packaging Icehouse for their 2.6-based releases."

This is the piece of info I needed to get on the same page -- thanks.

We'll move to both tweak our glance patch and play nicely with pbr so its not a 2.7 requirement.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-10-16 14:49:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Thomas Goirand's relevant comment (from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48475):

commit_message:
Remove ordereddict as a requirement

'ordereddict' was added as a potential requirement for Glance.
Glance no longer intends to use 'ordereddict' so this requirement can
be removed.

Thomas Goirand's relevant comment (from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48475):

  ordereddict will *not* be packaged for Debian or Ubuntu. While it is
  perfectly fine to use ordereddict *from* the integrated Python 2.7 support
  (collections.OrderedDict), since both Sid and Precise do not have Python
  2.6 anymore, it isn't correct at all to force the installation of an
  ordereddict package (with pip, apt or otherwise). Please avoid writing
  this as a hard requirement in any OpenStack packages.

The original commit which added 'ordereddict' was:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46474

Change-Id: Ia88d3536913f62be775558ec20766d27955462f9

commit_message:
Removes stubs from unit tests

self.stubs in TestCase and BaseTestCase classes use moxstubout
module which uses mox. OpenStack is moving to python 3 which
will not support mox. This patch removes the use of self.stubs
for all the unit test cases.

Change-Id: I0e5aa50edcbb1913c5143bb93efea965f5d5ebfb

commit_message:
Add a neutron parallel job

This commit adds a new run type for running an almost full gate with
neutron enabled, which is tempest-full - ~10 tests, (not counting
neutron skips in the tempest code) and runs it in parallel. In
addition this commit removes the testr-full run, since everything is
already running in parallel by default.

Change-Id: Ib69a30c3d6e87d3d27c0758502046370cfb5adcc

commit_message:
Fix huawei HVS driver QoS and Tier issues

Huawei HVS driver supports QOS and Tier functions. User can
open those functions by setting volume type. QOS requires users
to set flow strategy and io priority. Tier requires user to set
distribution policy and transfer strategy.

The current driver limits the QOS strategy to be "Qos-high",
"Qos-normal" and "Qos-low" which is not direct, and just allows
user to set distribution policy: "Tier-high", "Tier-normal" and
"Tier-low".

This patch changes the keys of QOS and Tier and adds transfer
strategy for Tier. Also it checks QOS strategy status when adding
new lun to the strategy.

Closes-bug: #1237268
Change-Id: Ib3daabc3a68da47d81b53857d3080158b5b574f4
(cherry picked from commit Ib3daabc3a68da47d81b53857d3080158b5b574f4)

commit_message:
Add python-six to requirements

missing python-six minimum version from the requirements.txt
set the min version to 1.4.1, without six recent versions of
keystone fail to start with a critical 'module' object has no
attribute 'add_metaclass' error

Change-Id: Ibfe2c9ec2457d3131dc9b6760e343c36ab8a3c38
Closes-Bug: #1237089

subject: Fix Huawei drivers to support other host OSs
messages: [{'account_id': 6604, 'date': '2013-10-16 14:15:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 13:52:16.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Huawei drivers to support other host OSs

Huawei drivers create Linux hosts by default when attaching volumes.
This patch makes them also support Windows, XenServer, AIX, etc.
The default OS is still Linux if it is not specified.

Users need to configure the host OS types in Huawei XML configuration
file. They need to set the items like this:
<Host OSType="Windows" HostIP="10.10.0.1, 10.10.0.2, ..." />
<Host .../>

When attaching a volume, the driver will get the host IP from nova. We
compare that IP with the IP in "HostIP" to get the corresponding OS type.

Closes-bug: #1229759
Change-Id: I36fd52b97f790f1c68eaf24b6c12e7ef5d16145d
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Huawei drivers to support other host OSs

Huawei drivers create Linux hosts by default when attaching volumes.
This patch makes them also support Windows, XenServer, AIX, etc.
The default OS is still Linux if it is not specified.

Users need to configure the host OS types in Huawei XML configuration
file. They need to set the items like this:
<Host OSType="Windows" HostIP="10.10.0.1, 10.10.0.2, ..." />
<Host .../>

When attaching a volume, the driver will get the host IP from nova. We
compare that IP with the IP in "HostIP" to get the corresponding OS type.

Closes-bug: #1229759
Change-Id: I36fd52b97f790f1c68eaf24b6c12e7ef5d16145d

commit_message:
Wrap map() to return list()

In Python 3, the map() function returns an iterator.
In Python 2, it returned a list.

Use list(map()) to fix the test_update/test_update_suffix errors
in py33 env.

Change-Id: I9d122fb5edf055ae0110e3a445d10733a817d7d2

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 09:03:36.000000000', 'message': 'Consolidate the use of stubs

We have two separate StubOutForTesting objects when running tests. One
that is instantiated directly in the moxstubout fixture and one that
mox has for itself.

When a method is stubbed, the overridden method is kept in a cache in
the StubOutForTesting instance. When calling UnsetAll() on this
instance, the order of the cache is reversed and the original methods
are put back in place. This means if you have SomeObject with a method
called actual_method and you stub that out with

    stubs.Set(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

you end up with a this tuple in the cache:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)

If you stub it out again

    stubs.Set(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method2)

this tuple is appended to the cache:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

When calling UnsetAll(), the cache is reversed and becomes:

    [(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method),
     (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)]

So first, SomeObject.actual_method (which currently is fake_method2) is
set to fake_method, and then set to the original
SomeObject.actual_method medthod.

If, however, you stub out the same method using both mox and our own
StubOutForTesting object, one of the caches will have

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)

and the other will have:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

At this point, restoring everything back to the original state depends
on these StubOutForTesting objects getting cleaned up in the correct
order. If it's done in the wrong order, SomeObject.actual_method
(currently set to fake_method2) will get reset to the original
SomeObject.actual_method and subsequently get "reset" to fake_method
which makes life miserable for subsequent tests that might rely on the
real implementation.

This change stops us from having two separate StubOutForTesting objects
by simply using mox's all the time.

Fixes bug #1239898

Change-Id: I3a768eca3432e6df09c87bd86bffa9763aabfbed

commit_message:
Consolidate the use of stubs

We have two separate StubOutForTesting objects when running tests. One
that is instantiated directly in the moxstubout fixture and one that
mox has for itself.

When a method is stubbed, the overridden method is kept in a cache in
the StubOutForTesting instance. When calling UnsetAll() on this
instance, the order of the cache is reversed and the original methods
are put back in place. This means if you have SomeObject with a method
called actual_method and you stub that out with

    stubs.Set(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

you end up with a this tuple in the cache:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)

If you stub it out again

    stubs.Set(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method2)

this tuple is appended to the cache:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

When calling UnsetAll(), the cache is reversed and becomes:

    [(SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method),
     (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)]

So first, SomeObject.actual_method (which currently is fake_method2) is
set to fake_method, and then set to the original
SomeObject.actual_method medthod.

If, however, you stub out the same method using both mox and our own
StubOutForTesting object, one of the caches will have

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", SomeObject.actual_method)

and the other will have:

    (SomeObject, "actual_method", fake_method)

At this point, restoring everything back to the original state depends
on these StubOutForTesting objects getting cleaned up in the correct
order. If it's done in the wrong order, SomeObject.actual_method
(currently set to fake_method2) will get reset to the original
SomeObject.actual_method and subsequently get "reset" to fake_method
which makes life miserable for subsequent tests that might rely on the
real implementation.

This change stops us from having two separate StubOutForTesting objects
by simply using mox's all the time.

Fixes bug #1239898

Change-Id: I3a768eca3432e6df09c87bd86bffa9763aabfbed

commit_message:
Add Availability Zone to Volume screens

User should be able to choose an AZ (or make unspecified) when creating a volume
AZ should be visible in Volumes table
AZ list should come from Cinder

Change-Id: I23314dedc3eb65454df32102b0a96174f8030d81
Closes-Bug: #1230288

commit_message:
Ignore H803 from Hacking.

H803 checks for a period in commit messages, something the community
clearly rejected as a sensible check: periods in commit messages
should neither be rejected or required.

Change-Id: I754e10ca01b3e6f8c6482e1bcd4c2e2ca8c1cfc9

commit_message:
Don't allow updates when another action is in-progress

It doesn't make sense to do this, and will lead to a really
confused state.

Change-Id: I8681a3f0023a91bed4fac246fe37a131b07aefe2

Do not attempt a stack update when it is suspended

And in any state (inprogress, complete, failed).

Closes-bug: #1234242

Enable exception format checking when testing

Enable FATAL_EXCEPTION_FORMAT_ERRORS so that we are checking
exception formats while testing. This should help guard against
exception format errors when testing.

commit_message:
Replace deprecated method aliases in tests

Some of the TestCase methods have been deprecated since python 2.7.
We need use correct names.

http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases

* replace 'assertEquals' with 'assertEqual'
* replace 'failUnlessAlmostEqual' with 'assertAlmostEqual'

Change-Id: I90da87723e3e36767946d276301b75af801b952d

commit_message:
Setup storage pipeline in the boostrap instead of driver base

This patch moves pipeline setup into the bootstrap and out of
the storage driver base class, so that the base class can be
inherited by meta-drivers, such as the planned sharding manager,
without introducing a loop in the bootstrapping logic.

Now, a meta-driver is exposed to the transport object that
takes care of wiring up the pipeline for each resource
controller behind the scenes.

As part of this work, the pipeline config was modified to
support configuring different stages depending on the
resource. We create three instances of Pipeline anyway,
so it seemed to make sense to allow the operator to
configure the pipelines independently.

Partially-Implements: blueprint storage-pipeline
Change-Id: Ibdb7d0e9537b1eec38a13f4881df7462039bbf98
