commit_message:
Implement the SubnetId property in the Instance resource

If the SubnetId parameter is given in the template, the handle_create method
in the Instance resource verifies the subnet in quantum and configures the
NetworkInterfaces for the subnet. If no NetworkInterface is specified, a port
is created for the subnet and the nic is configured to use that port.

Porting this fix into stable/grizzly

(cherry picked from commit 58d88f64d79ecc336a15e5898b1de1efd605f112)
Conflicts:
    heat/engine/resources/autoscaling.py
    heat/tests/test_instance.py
    heat/tests/test_instance_network.py

Change-Id: I92da0800565392004c4f75ad186f67b638df2df1
Fixes: bug #1163952

commit_message:
Encode values as utf-8 before encrypting

Ensure strings are correctly encoded before encrypting

This is necessary because some encryption libraries don't handle
the unicode conversion appropriately.

Also includes "tolerate None values to _encrypt" fix from
bug #1237596, without which the grizzly unit tests fail

Conflicts:
    heat/db/sqlalchemy/api.py
    heat/heat/tests/test_sqlalchemy_api.py

Combination of these Change-Id's,
Iebbf32e57ba21d955c1984ee32360379579366c8
I39cd4a1bab39def9ad4c214da768e91f411d7697
with a partial backport (one test) from
Ie0fdc5068475db7e84f366d1eb2b9ae56db0b3fc
to ensure test-coverage of the bugfix.

Closes-Bug: #1237596
Closes-Bug: #1207707
Change-Id: I1efaedc983b60a01944d5ebf88084f52ba909e78

commit_message:
Make DevstackEngine work out of the box

Currently there is some requirements for host:

* user 'rally' is exists and in sudoers with NOPASSWD.
* git is installed

With this change all this stuff is doing automatically.

Change-Id: I79f5bd7e291adb68cf944ae75afdf0bd79765258

commit_message:
glance image v1 member test cleaup

* Use private (not public) image for image member tests
* Use the alt_users tenant not a randomly selected tenant
* Increase the verbosity of the assertEqual int the test_remove_member

Change-Id: I3aac82f59e09998bf938ac364671d3d944d47a62

commit_message:
Flesh cinder install section

The cinder install section previously only had package install

It splits out controller sections from a block storage node
where the disk lives.

this patch adds database, endpoint creation, service restarts.

what's needed: block1: creation of volume group, tgt setup
(suggest following http://devstack.org/lib/cinder.html)

both: setting driver and key manager

as usual, if fifieldt is not on IRC this patch is up for grabs

Change-Id: I313e696881618561bdd7cbd8d5c5db1eccbde4e1

commit_message:
Use traditional init script commands for openSUSE

These changes allow sharing the code of Fedora with openSUSE
and also SLES.

Also, tag some openSUSE changes with sles as well, more
to come.

Change-Id: I6b7fb9fb271e4ddbf267a09b2f10c4c968ef7092

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-15 22:58:25.000000000', 'message': 'Fix v2 token user ref with trust impersonation=True

The v2 token controller incorrectly checks for a string instead
of a boolean, which results in the wrong user ID (trustee, when
it should be the trustor) when impersonation=True.  So fix the
comparison and tests, adding a test which illustrates the issue.

Change-Id: Ic94f30f2354c9fda20531bb598387368fde8a096
Closes-Bug: #1239303
'}]
commit_message:
Fix v2 token user ref with trust impersonation=True

The v2 token controller incorrectly checks for a string instead
of a boolean, which results in the wrong user ID (trustee, when
it should be the trustor) when impersonation=True.  So fix the
comparison and tests, adding a test which illustrates the issue.

Change-Id: Ic94f30f2354c9fda20531bb598387368fde8a096
Closes-Bug: #1239303

[{'created': '2013-10-14 13:25:18.000000000', 'message': "Scrap nonsense provider setting requirements

Currently, if any provider setting is defined, it's enforced that
the other settings are defined as well. This is wrong and in some
cases even contradicts with Neutron.

Different settings need to be either present or absent depending on
the various network types. It would be a huge overkill to validate
all the possible combinations, particularly since relying on
Neutron to do the proper checks is good enough.

Change-Id: I36ad13da6d796d79e5d0050a13f1766455b478be
"}]
commit_message:
Scrap nonsense provider setting requirements

Currently, if any provider setting is defined, it's enforced that
the other settings are defined as well. This is wrong and in some
cases even contradicts with Neutron.

Different settings need to be either present or absent depending on
the various network types. It would be a huge overkill to validate
all the possible combinations, particularly since relying on
Neutron to do the proper checks is good enough.

Change-Id: I36ad13da6d796d79e5d0050a13f1766455b478be

commit_message:
Remove obsolete code of urlparse importing

Python 2.5 is not supported anymore, urlparse is useless in
keystoneclient/httpclient.py file.

keystoneclient is depended by a dozen othere projects, "import urlparse"
will induce py33 issue in these projects.

So, clear it up.

Close-Bug #1239956

Change-Id: I76b00f9594a52f4826c0c66eca58210755afd9ba

commit_message:
Don't zero out thin provisioned LV's on delete

Thin provisioned LV's don't need secure delete to protect
from data leakage.  Also, zeroing these out kinda defeats
the purpose of using thing provisioning.

This patch add a check for the lvm type and if it's thin simply
returns from the lvm.clear_volume() method.

Change-Id: Ie6764209018152565295291efc6fbba553698ae6
Closes-Bug: #1240299

commit_message:
Nexenta NFS volume driver folder auto sharing

1. Auto sharing for NFS enclosing folders, this helps to avoid errors if user
forgot to share enclosing directory.

2. Added version history to NexentaNfsDriver doc string.

Change-Id: I9aa2a7b8760c687985aa11d85715188f1c1622f9

commit_message:
Cancel an ongoing server snapshot

During an instance snapshot, the instance can be stuck in particular
task state when the image uploading takes time or restart of compute
during the snapshot. This would prevent users from taking any further
action on the instance like a resize or rebuild.

The os-server-image-cancel extension exposes an endpoint to cancel an
ongoing server snapshot. As part of the cancel, the instance task state
would be set to 'None', image deleted from glance and the image
uploading would be cancelled if started. This functionality has been
implemented for xenserver only.

Implements: blueprint cancel-an-ongoing-image

Change-Id: I217b16479e5fda6195ffa974310daa04d124cb4b

commit_message:
Fix baremetal volume driver to work

To get fixed-ips for the instance, it uses network API instead of
DB API. Also updated to suit underlying LibVirt iSCSI volume driver.

Also adds tests for the volume driver.

Change-Id: Ia6198c864bd25c3189cd533154bb383ab68c5060
Closes-Bug: #1208707

VMware: add support for the driver

Add VC driver support to the stable/grizzly version. The motivation is
to ensure that CI for the VC driver runs on this version too.

[{'created': '2013-09-11 19:06:46.000000000', 'message': "Interface-attach: properly refresh cache

Since commit 394c693e359ed4f19cc2f7d975b1f9ee5500b7f6 ,
allocate_port_for_instance() has been returning only the latest allocated port,
instead of __all__ the allocated ports. Its return value is used to refresh the
cache (thanks to the 'refresh_cache' decorator), thus leading said cache to
hold wrong data.

This patch makes _get_instance_nw_info() refresh the cache, and removes the
decorator from both allocate_port_for_instance() and allocate_for_instance() to
fix the issue. The deallocate_port_for_instance() method therefore does not
need this decorator any more, so remove it as well.

Change-Id: I02fc0ee3fcfb01fa473fb8d899d8349143e55b3e
Closes-Bug: #1223859
"}]
commit_message:
Interface-attach: properly refresh cache

Since commit 394c693e359ed4f19cc2f7d975b1f9ee5500b7f6 ,
allocate_port_for_instance() has been returning only the latest allocated port,
instead of __all__ the allocated ports. Its return value is used to refresh the
cache (thanks to the 'refresh_cache' decorator), thus leading said cache to
hold wrong data.

This patch makes _get_instance_nw_info() refresh the cache, and removes the
decorator from both allocate_port_for_instance() and allocate_for_instance() to
fix the issue. The deallocate_port_for_instance() method therefore does not
need this decorator any more, so remove it as well.

Change-Id: I02fc0ee3fcfb01fa473fb8d899d8349143e55b3e
Closes-Bug: #1223859

commit_message:
Add stack id and resource id in logs

Where applicable, the stack and resource id's will be added in the logs that
reference those stacks and/or resources.

blueprint log-resource-stack-id

[{'created': '2013-10-08 08:38:59.000000000', 'message': 'remove skip-networking from my.cnf file

This patch will modify the my.cnf file to turn off the option
skip-networking.  If skip-networking is on then devstack will be
unable to connect to the mysql server as it does so through TCP
sockets.

Change-Id: I5424d12b2a4e27c3272878e4bfeb99290aaca633
Closes-Bug: #1236740
'}]
commit_message:
remove skip-networking from my.cnf file

This patch will modify the my.cnf file to turn off the option
skip-networking.  If skip-networking is on then devstack will be
unable to connect to the mysql server as it does so through TCP
sockets.

Change-Id: I5424d12b2a4e27c3272878e4bfeb99290aaca633
Closes-Bug: #1236740

commit_message:
Update node_id to node_uuid

our options require a *_id while *-create and *-show report uuids.
This patch updates all to use uuid.

Change-Id: Ie963d4242c45288dc9eba7d00ca1d4abd0ce821f

commit_message:
Add port bindings to ports created in Midonet

Currently Midokura uses its own script (mm-ctl) to bind ports. However, support
for using this script is left out of the nova and neutron projects. This causes
confusion and makes deployments unnecessarily complicated for customers using
Havana. This fix is to change Neutron to properly set up port bindings to use
the "midonet" vif driver when creating a port. Corresponding changes will be
submitted to the devstack and Nova projects.

Change-Id: I91f2e4fe7135da0c22fb408081efdc63fff748df
Closes-Bug: 1235134

commit_message:
Info about enabling and disabling a service included in admin guide

about the new '--reason' parameter for Compute which allows user to

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 03:33:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fix lvm.extend_volume to pass Gig suffix

The extend function in the lvm driver was not converting
the cinder size value to Gigabytes before passing the call
to the vg module.  The result was that we would attempt to
extend a volume to "new size in Megabytes" which of course
is less than the current size since we do a Gigabyte string
conversion on create and everywhere else.

This change makes sure we pass the integer change through
the sizestr method to get the G suffix needed to work properly.

Change-Id: I070962a3aa7038f612e19a93ccaa60cbc13008f6
Closes-Bug: #1240287
(cherry picked from commit ec442e41d2d243003a42ed60ae862e96142a5cde)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix lvm.extend_volume to pass Gig suffix

The extend function in the lvm driver was not converting
the cinder size value to Gigabytes before passing the call
to the vg module.  The result was that we would attempt to
extend a volume to "new size in Megabytes" which of course
is less than the current size since we do a Gigabyte string
conversion on create and everywhere else.

This change makes sure we pass the integer change through
the sizestr method to get the G suffix needed to work properly.

Change-Id: I070962a3aa7038f612e19a93ccaa60cbc13008f6
Closes-Bug: #1240287
(cherry picked from commit ec442e41d2d243003a42ed60ae862e96142a5cde)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-09 19:36:58.000000000', 'message': 'Fix 500 from account-quota middleware

If a user had set X-Account-Meta-Quota-Bytes to something non-integer
prior to the installation of the account-quota middleware, then the
quota check would choke on it. Now a non-integer value is treated as
"no quota".

Change-Id: I5c38911be1f66fa293aea9c78590d4ce7d184113
'}]
commit_message:
Fix 500 from account-quota middleware

If a user had set X-Account-Meta-Quota-Bytes to something non-integer
prior to the installation of the account-quota middleware, then the
quota check would choke on it. Now a non-integer value is treated as
"no quota".

Change-Id: I5c38911be1f66fa293aea9c78590d4ce7d184113

commit_message:
Fix Huawei drivers to support other host OSs

Huawei drivers create Linux hosts by default when attaching volumes.
This patch makes them also support Windows, XenServer, AIX, etc.
The default OS is still Linux if it is not specified.

Users need to configure the host OS types in Huawei XML configuration
file. They need to set the items like this:
<Host OSType="Windows" HostIP="10.10.0.1, 10.10.0.2, ..." />
<Host .../>

When attaching a volume, the driver will get the host IP from nova. We
compare that IP with the IP in "HostIP" to get the corresponding OS type.

Closes-bug: #1229759
Change-Id: I36fd52b97f790f1c68eaf24b6c12e7ef5d16145d

Handle VLAN interfaces with Linux IP wrapper

Check if the interface name contains '@' character and use the part

commit_message:
Add warning explaining sf_user_prefix option

There's an issue with HA environments and the default
config options used for the SolidFire driver.  The SolidFire
driver creates a unique account on the cluster for each tenant,
by default this account name is : <$hostname>-<$tenant-id>

This works great, unless you're in an HA env, in which case there are
two possible accounts that are valid.  Also in the case of upgrading
or migrating your cinder-volume service to a new node, the result is that
the formation of the account name is now for the "new" hostname and users
loose access to their existing volumes that they created on the "old" host.

Change-Id: Id2ffc268e59810decc85f8da4ec41e4b751d65ff

[{'created': '2013-10-16 01:16:35.000000000', 'message': 'Fix lvm.extend_volume to pass Gig suffix

The extend function in the lvm driver was not converting
the cinder size value to Gigabytes before passing the call
to the vg module.  The result was that we would attempt to
extend a volume to "new size in Megabytes" which of course
is less than the current size since we do a Gigabyte string
conversion on create and everywhere else.

This change makes sure we pass the integer change through
the sizestr method to get the G suffix needed to work properly.

Change-Id: I070962a3aa7038f612e19a93ccaa60cbc13008f6
Closes-Bug: #1240287
'}]
commit_message:
Fix lvm.extend_volume to pass Gig suffix

The extend function in the lvm driver was not converting
the cinder size value to Gigabytes before passing the call
to the vg module.  The result was that we would attempt to
extend a volume to "new size in Megabytes" which of course
is less than the current size since we do a Gigabyte string
conversion on create and everywhere else.

This change makes sure we pass the integer change through
the sizestr method to get the G suffix needed to work properly.

Change-Id: I070962a3aa7038f612e19a93ccaa60cbc13008f6
Closes-Bug: #1240287

commit_message:
Make SecurityGroup receive context

This fixes the SecurityGroup._from_db_object() method to take and set
a context, like most everything else.

Change-Id: Ie86df2cf264a1e75353599a8f9f693ef5fb15bc5

commit_message:
Fix DB API mismatch with sqlalchemy API

We added a sqlalchemy columns_to_join argument to the
security_group_get_by_name() method, but didn't punch it through
the toplevel DB API. This patch adds that so that they match.

Change-Id: I6fe8d876834036e6fbd79d60f3d7d696d7cf4b83

commit_message:
Initialize shares variables for RemoteFsDriver(s)

self.shares and self._mounted_shares are used by various methods
for RemoteFs-based drivers, but may not be instantiated early enough.

Initialize them in __init__ to ensure they always exist.  (Also fixes
pylint warnings.)

Closes-Bug: #1239741
Change-Id: I0ef884c28b82b7f694cf8a0fb4629c835da11c91

match, rather than remove the comment.

"}, {'created': '2013-10-14 23:21:44.000000000', 'message': "Fix scheduler rpcapi deprecated method comment

necessary to bump the version... and the manager side wasn't bumped.
It's still at 2.9.

Change-Id: I52857f5a2e472dbdf13b9b6a51a9e8f401ea6452
"}]
commit_message:
Fix scheduler rpcapi deprecated method comment

A comment was added for 2.10 about deprecating a method.  It's not
necessary to bump the version... and the manager side wasn't bumped.
It's still at 2.9.

Just remove the reference to the 2.10 version.

Change-Id: I52857f5a2e472dbdf13b9b6a51a9e8f401ea6452

commit_message:
Send notifications on keypair create/delete

A service external to Nova may wany to know when users add or delete
keypairs.  This patch adds create and delete notifications to the
KeypairAPI.

Implements blueprint keypair-notifications

Change-Id: I8e0d74e73b1980689c11d9e3567b9883018951cc

commit_message:
Sanitize passwords when logging payload in wsgi

adminPass (or admin_pass) can be either part of a json object or
an xml element or xml attribute. The patch includes
regexps to support all these cases and adds tests
as well

Change-Id: Ic119f986a03863c1d13b566b4c005f3bc77d83d0
Closes-Bug: 1231263

commit_message:
Handle MarkerNotFound better in Flavor API

When the specified marker is not found, we should catch the
MarkerNotFound exception and respond with a HTTP 400 Bad
Request with sufficient information back to the user. This
will avoid spilling unwanted tracebacks in the logs as well.

Change-Id: I90a658384f8814096271a193a0f3abd028062b5d
Partial-Bug: 1238519

commit_message:
Fixes datastore selection bug

Currently the vmwareapi drivers will only select the first
available datastore it finds, even when there are other
datastores with capacity, it will fill one datastore completely
and then die.

Closes-bug: 1227825

Change-Id: I24f85114ea3f014950c27c0c91a6be352990d263

commit_message:
Fix i18n issue for nova/virt/baremetal/virtual_power_driver.py

There are some log messages in virtual_power_driver.py does not
support i18n, we need to update code to support it.

Closes-bug: #1228449

Change-Id: I6642309bd0e08e356a13d134ac0c743159af2520

I agree with Mark, I don't buy the "bundle to reduce review load" thing either.'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-10-15 02:44:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (4 inline comments)

Re: bundling - we had about 50 api samples to merge in H3 and I was concerned about the review load they would cause - and most of them did end up going in pretty smoothly given that problems were found in review before core reviewers got to them. In this case all of them ended up needing to be updated anyway because of changes which merged in the meantime. That being said since there's a bit of a lull now I've split them up into separate changesets.

Re: copy & paste. I realise this is a big maintenance issue but I've really tried to choose the least worst solution for the v2/v3 transition. 

The basic infrastructure is shared for the api sample tests. For the non api sample integrated tests where I thought there was a lot more in common I did use inheritance to share a lot more of the test code and ended up getting review feedback saying they thought the copy & paste method was better."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-10-15 02:45:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-15 03:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

[{'created': '2013-10-15 23:06:11.000000000', 'message': 'FK lookup failures during migration

There are a couple of cases where migrations have failed
upgrading from Grizzly to Havana, this seems to be isolated
to a couple of migrations so far and the error message is a
failure to lookup/associate the volume-id FK dependency.

It appears that this is caused by not setting the charset
in the migration, so the result is that the initial db setup
uses utf8 and the migrations are using the default latin1.

This patch goes through all of the migrations in Havana that
specify InnoDB and explicitly sets the charset to utf8 to match
the volumes table (and the other original tables).

Change-Id: I43b219ff5e4eea10a7391ad65ef68a80b7460370
Closes-Bug: #1233861
(cherry picked from commit 645a84f990c90e28548cf35b4b5f242eb0e0c286)
'}]
commit_message:
FK lookup failures during migration

There are a couple of cases where migrations have failed
upgrading from Grizzly to Havana, this seems to be isolated
to a couple of migrations so far and the error message is a
failure to lookup/associate the volume-id FK dependency.

It appears that this is caused by not setting the charset
in the migration, so the result is that the initial db setup
uses utf8 and the migrations are using the default latin1.

This patch goes through all of the migrations in Havana that
specify InnoDB and explicitly sets the charset to utf8 to match
the volumes table (and the other original tables).

Change-Id: I43b219ff5e4eea10a7391ad65ef68a80b7460370
Closes-Bug: #1233861
(cherry picked from commit 645a84f990c90e28548cf35b4b5f242eb0e0c286)

Migrate to Oslo DB 96d1f887dda Part 3

Oslo version 96d1f887dda21b43ba4376187f31953dee6f5273

This commit just migrates Heat to new db related code from Oslo

Partially implements blueprint oslo-db-support

Change-Id: Ib0de40a70857fb3e029a2282f06746269a628c71

I'm also concerned that the sleep calls inside transactions could hurt server throughput by extending transaction time, even if they don't cause any actual errors. I'd like to hear from Mark on this, but think the changes to both files are important to get into RC2 if possible."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:05:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Regarding the change in extra route db, I think it is okay as a temporary fix, though this change potentially contains inconsistent update of router.
Ideally the db operation and RPC in update_router in l3_db should be split. The similar approach to add hook methods as ML2 plugin adopts may be one of the answers.

I have the similar concern about calling greenthread.sleep() in transactions. I think it leads to longer transaction and increases potential possibility of failures/race condition of transactions, though I am not very familiar with this area.'}, {'account_id': 8655, 'date': '2013-10-15 09:12:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 8655, 'date': '2013-10-15 09:14:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Removing rpc communication from db transaction

In a transaction context of ExtraRoute_db_mixin.update_router() was
called super method that uses subtransaction and communication with l3
agent. In case of agent's heartbeat happens while there is running
transaction, update heartbeat in agents table gets stuck in a deadlock.

Closes-Bug: #1211915
Change-Id: I96e6a9d7172d5a0e3e720a81fcd10f04c40aef07

commit_message:
Pull in toci_cleanup from toci

This can be used to remove VM's and storage from previous runs of
devtest.sh and will be placed in devtest to make sure a previous run
doesn't interfere with the current run.

commit_message:
Fix conductor rpcapi deprecated method comment

A comment was added for 1.59 about deprecating a method.  It's not
necessary to bump the version... and the manager side wasn't bumped.
It's still at 1.58.

Just remove the reference to the version.

Change-Id: I3b3eca72acc28f0c29f8dff8402937eab7152a37

commit_message:
Make pypi-mirror more secure and robust

There's no reason we need to run this mirror as root, so run it as a
system user. Also it is creating a cache of removable data, which really
belongs in /var/cache, so we put the data there instead of /opt/stack.

Change-Id: I47d436733e9dd6ca0bebc25bf577e6d749d36f35

commit_message:
Make XenAPI use Aggregate object

This makes the XenAPI driver use the Aggregate object for its work,
and avoids the need to call back through virtapi to conductor
directly. It also allows us to convert the two aggregate-related
compute manager methods fully to new-world objects.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects
Related to blueprint virt-objects

Closes-bug: #1232179
Change-Id: Ib38ab0e4d6feefebda37888f150752167474b693

commit_message:
Split out unit tests as separate tox jobs

This commit removes the tempest unit tests from the same tox job as
the tempest runs. It creates a separate py26, py27, and py33 tox job
for running the unit tests.

Change-Id: I9efea4cfa42f770c34869c0b0931b0ed0b51c177

commit_message:
Consolidates TestCase and BaseTestCase

Most unit tests are derived from TestCase class of base.py.
A few unit tests are derived from BaseTestCase class of utils.py.
This patch consolidates these two classes into one and have all
the tests derived from a single base class which is TestCase class.
Hence, the ironic/tests/util.py is removed from this patch.

Change-Id: Iecc3352ef7e49524b202e6551a233692a2f6acea

commit_message:
Fix seed network setup.

I missed a setup-neutron call when adding bare metal metadata routes.
Also changed the order of parameters to neutron so SUBNET_EXTRA is last
and parsed correctly.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podolyaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-15 20:01:50.000000000', 'message': 'FK lookup failures during migration

There are a couple of cases where migrations have failed
upgrading from Grizlly to Havana, this seems to be isolated
to a couple of migrations so far and the error message is a
failure to lookup/associate the volume-id FK dependency.

It appears that this is caused by not setting the charset
in the migration, so the result is that the initial db setup
uses utf8 and the migrations are using the default latin1.

This patch goes through all of the migrations in Havana that
specify InnoDB and explicitly sets the charset to utf8 to match
the volumes table (and the other original tables).

Change-Id: I43b219ff5e4eea10a7391ad65ef68a80b7460370
Closes-Bug: #1233861
'}, {'created': '2013-10-15 20:47:10.000000000', 'message': 'FK lookup failures during migration

commit_message:
FK lookup failures during migration

There are a couple of cases where migrations have failed
upgrading from Grizzly to Havana, this seems to be isolated
to a couple of migrations so far and the error message is a
failure to lookup/associate the volume-id FK dependency.

It appears that this is caused by not setting the charset
in the migration, so the result is that the initial db setup
uses utf8 and the migrations are using the default latin1.

This patch goes through all of the migrations in Havana that
specify InnoDB and explicitly sets the charset to utf8 to match
the volumes table (and the other original tables).

Change-Id: I43b219ff5e4eea10a7391ad65ef68a80b7460370
Closes-Bug: #1233861

commit_message:
Update short description language

There is a legal/english thing that needs to happen here - it can't be
"OpenStack Benchmark System" due to trademark issues unless it's
blessed. It can be "Benchmark System for OpenStack" - which I think
should be about the same.

Change-Id: I1b015dbbe68dbeed8ddf7bf393456a399a5a6340

It should be possible to authenticate against the v2 tokens
API with a trust_id, because it suports rescoping an existing
token to a trust, this patch adds client support for this.

Note with the current keystone code it's necessary to pass the

c = client_v2.Client(username=TRUSTEE_USERNAME,

commit_message:
Allow v2 client authentication with trust_id

It should be possible to authenticate against the v2 tokens
API with a trust_id, because it suports rescoping an existing
token to a trust, this patch adds client support for this.

Note with the current keystone code it's necessary to pass the
trustor tenant ID when rescoping with a trust where
impersonation==True, e.g:

c = client_v2.Client(username=TRUSTEE_USERNAME,
                     password=TRUSTEE_USERNAME,
                     tenant_name=TRUSTEE_TENANT_NAME,
                     auth_url=OS_AUTH_URL_V2)
c.authenticate(trust_id=trust_i.id, tenant_id=TRUSTOR_TENANT_ID)

Change-Id: I177c41af298b7437e2c6fb437aa9ce9a09773b9d
Closes-Bug: #1231483

commit_message:
Further openSUSE instructions

dashboard: Explain database session store is configured by default

heat:
* Fix setup
* openstack-db does not handle heat yet, remove its usage

ceilometer:
* Fix setup
* Fix service startup commands

Fix passwords: it's _PASS for the keystone password and
_DBPASS for the database one.

heat and ceilometer installation has been tested but this does
not work completely yet. Need first a working network install.

Change-Id: I8007b79dd109e7e41aa45735f5044e723604faf9

commit_message:
Fix v2 token user ref with trust impersonation=True

The v2 token controller incorrectly checks for a string instead
of a boolean, which results in the wrong user ID (trustee, when
it should be the trustor) when impersonation=True.  So fix the
comparison and tests, adding a test which illustrates the issue.

Change-Id: Ic94f30f2354c9fda20531bb598387368fde8a096
Closes-Bug: #1239303

commit_message:
Check for VM ERROR state rather than FAILED

Check for VM status of ERROR rather than FAILED in nova benchmark utils.
Also a simple unit test to validate the status is detected.

Closes-Bug: 1240093

Change-Id: Id1f9f66f6bfc9bb1e37a0b151d330193a20f225d

commit_message:
Rename tests to _tests

PEP8 says that internal modules should be prefixed with _. Since
tests is not a public module it should be prefixed with _.

See http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#public-and-internal-interfaces

Change-Id: If1609bc5432986be1bf7ebee20f8a5e259eeac8e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-12 14:17:12.000000000', 'message': 'xeanpi: ensure private ip listed in config drive

Currently the ec2 metadata in config drive does not include the
local-ipv4 address, because the address is not passed in when using
config drive.

commit_message:
populate local-ipv4 address in config drive

Currently the ec2 metadata in config drive does not include the
local-ipv4 address, because the address is not passed in when using
config drive.

This change uses the fixed_ips in network_info to populate the address
if the address was not passed in.

Fixes bug 1221664
Change-Id: I1b289bbbd7ebe103342909079d2488cf1dfbf472

commit_message:
Make os-cache retry on an invalid token

client.authenticate doesn't actually do any rest calls if a token is present,
it just assumes the token is valid.  Instead re-authentication is done if the
request raises an Unauthorized exception, at which point we want to
unauthenticate (delete the token from in-memory) and overwrite the old token
in the keyring. Also if a password is present allways pass it into the client
so re-authentication is possible during _cs_request.

Change-Id: I86d0356d5685ffa802f1bdc97e33727ff2dd075e

commit_message:
Document and make OS_CACHE work

Before the --os-no-cache option logic would overwrite any value set in env['OS_CACHE'].
Since os-no-cache  is deprecated, and also the default value, just remove it.
Also update the help message for --os-cache to mention the environment variable.

Change-Id: Ie2569d5cdf0f12f3a29e9a6f20faef75956d2209

In get_localized_message we were only updating a Message's locale if it
was not None, but None is also a valid request, it means the default.
If a Message had been previously translated and since None was ignored,
the message was translated to the last translated locale. This patch
fixes that.

Change-Id: I8e1a594d779d18c88dc42c612900442d191bfa70
"}, {'created': '2013-10-09 19:35:20.000000000', 'message': "When translating if no locale is given use default locale

In get_localized_message we were only updating a Message's locale if it
was not None, but None is also a valid request, it means the default.
If a Message had been previously translated and since None was ignored,
the message was translated to the last translated locale. This patch
fixes that. It also makes sure that the given message object's locale is
not changed after translation.

Change-Id: I8e1a594d779d18c88dc42c612900442d191bfa70
"}]
commit_message:
When translating if no locale is given use default locale

In get_localized_message we were only updating a Message's locale if it
was not None, but None is also a valid request, it means the default.
If a Message had been previously translated and since None was ignored,
the message was translated to the last translated locale. This patch
fixes that. It also makes sure that the given message object's locale is
not changed after translation.

Change-Id: I8e1a594d779d18c88dc42c612900442d191bfa70

Revert "Add-in some re-auth logic when using os_cache"

This patch didn't do what it was supposed to do, make os_cache work. Instead it just adds complexity, so just remove it.

'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-15 02:21:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Who is "we" and why wasn't this setting already info?'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-15 11:31:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

My general preference is for the default to be WARN. Logging every single request seems a bit verbose no?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-15 11:47:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The commit message is a little misleading, since using warning level will result in more verbose output than using info.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-15 11:48:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Oh, unless the option means that the logger for that one module is configured to emit messages at the specified level?'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 15:20:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Doug, the we is confusing sorry. 'we' would be openstack if you agree with this. I should have not used the word we.  Once there is agreement on what this patch should actually do, I will update the commit message.

Dan,for debugging we want to log every transaction. And I think we want that even during a real deployment, because this along with request-ids makes it easy to find a users request inside the logs.  Perhaps a better approach is to not use a custom log level for eventlet.wsgi.server at all.

As a side note nova and cinder don't use the eventlet.wsgi.server logger so this is a moot point for them."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-15 15:43:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I thought that's probably what you meant by "we" but wanted to make sure there wasn't a discussion I had missed. :-)

I don't have a problem with the change. It does sound like we may need some more thought about whether to customize it at all or leave it up to the deployer's logging config. Should we move this to the mailing list?'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 18:01:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Doug,

This change doesn't affect nova or cinder which don't use the eventlet.wsgi.server logger. So as is we already have a non-uniform solution (Our log files are very different across services and this is a small step to fix that -- for example see http://logs.openstack.org/61/50861/1/check/check-tempest-devstack-vm-neutron/fe420fa/logs/).   And I think not customizing will result in the most intuitive result. And a deployer can still change the setting if they prefer.

I don't think this needs a ML discussion, but I don't object to one so I am happy to move this discussion there."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:12:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:13:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Joe and I discussed this on IRC. It seems like we should just let the standard logging config file manage these settings, but we didn't want to remove the option without looking into why it was created in the first place. Removing the override for eventlet seemed like a good compromise."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

default log_format:

%(status_code)s %(body_length)s %(wall_seconds).6f'

Change-Id: I42124793bbf542d69f6493bb3a9611e443775c2a
'}, {'created': '2013-10-15 19:12:04.000000000', 'message': "Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging

We want eventlet.wsgi.server to use the same log level as everything
else (by default). For example if INFO logging is enabled eventlet.wsgi.server will
log all API requests. So if INFO logging is enabled in the API server we
want eventlet.wsgi.server to use the same log level.

This only changes a default value, and can be set by the user.

Change-Id: I42124793bbf542d69f6493bb3a9611e443775c2a
"}]
commit_message:
Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging

We want eventlet.wsgi.server to use the same log level as everything
else (by default). For example if INFO logging is enabled eventlet.wsgi.server will
log all API requests. So if INFO logging is enabled in the API server we
want eventlet.wsgi.server to use the same log level.

This only changes a default value, and can be set by the user.

Change-Id: I42124793bbf542d69f6493bb3a9611e443775c2a

commit_message:
Also allow "_" to be valid identifier

A "_" is a valid python identifier as long as it
is not the first letter of the given attribute (as
an attribute dict doesn't have the concept of
protected/private variables).

Also include a few links and comments as to why
the restrictions are inplace.

Change-Id: I23f17113cedb99b2817bad0c464a43d10af6722c

commit_message:
Add parsing into config.py to see if ceph deployed

For now tests skipeed if there is no cinder node.
But it is not correct when ceph deployed as a volume storage
Add parsing of nailgun response if the cheph deployed
Add verification in test

Fix bug PRD-2087

Change-Id: I921bff6f15c1891012e802c1569b3ae0ec17d08a

[{'created': '2013-10-09 19:48:58.000000000', 'message': 'horizon is removing the URL path from glance's endpoint

Autor: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Glanceclient removes the API version from the endpoint in case it exists. Look the following code:

https://github.com/openstack/python-glanceclient/blob/master/glanceclient/shell.py#L310

    def _strip_version(self, endpoint):
        """Strip version from the last component of endpoint if present."""

        # Get rid of trailing '/' if present
        if endpoint.endswith('/'):
            endpoint = endpoint[:-1]
        url_bits = endpoint.split('/')
        # regex to match 'v1' or 'v2.0' etc
        if re.match('v\d+\.?\d*', url_bits[-1]):
            endpoint = '/'.join(url_bits[:-1])
        return endpoint

The rest of code includes the API version in use accordingly.

Change-Id: I7a393fbb6ed82aad3756c2a231cc693a0e86e217

Remove KeypairManager.get monkey patch

commit_message:
Fix root disk not be detached after deleting lxc container

Add teardown_container action when cleanup lxc instance to make
sure root disk be detached and no resource leak.

Fixes: bug #1208387
       bug #1203927

Change-Id: I063fd3a9856bba089bcde5cdefd2576e2eb2b0e9

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issue with VHD file format

The VHD format cookie signature needs to be checked in the footer
instead of the header as fixed format VHDs don't have a copy of the
footer at the beginning of the file.

Fixes bug: #1233853

Change-Id: Ibe44f0d895cde2edbc03dcd6ecebac24b0936660

commit_message:
Further harden boto version checking in EC2 tests

Use pkg_resources to determine correct boto interface
to use in API tests.  stable/grizzly version.

Fixes Bug #1239220

'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-09 13:57:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

I cleaned up some errors in the WADL and pulled the code samples into separate files. Once this change goes through for clouddocs-mvn-plugin (https://github.com/rackerlabs/clouddocs-maven-plugin/pull/97), the metering API will appear on the jump menu. You'll need to update the pom.xml file to point to 1.11.1 clouddocs-mvn-plugin then."}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-09 15:21:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

OK, so what I haven't told you is that the WADL file is generated by a Sphinx extension I wrote (I haven't released it yet, because I need to make it's ok with the legal department) from the RST files in Ceilometer.

The examples are a leftover of some debugging of mine. Since they are not in Ceilometer yet, I'd like to remove them for now.

Other changes involve having the "wadl:doc" elements before the "request" and "response" elements. I could make my doc generator do that.

I see you've changed some of the ids ('get_v2_alarms_method' -> 'listAlarms', for instance). Do you really want that ? What are the rules to name ids ?

Did I miss any other changes ?'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-09 19:49:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Cyril, 

Yes, I really wanted to change the names of the IDs since some of the IDs were causing failures. (And the original names were not user-friendly.) I also moved the code samples to separate files, but that's not necessary."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2013-10-10 03:05:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-10 11:31:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

OK, so I made sure my doc generator writes the 'wadl:doc' element before the 'request' and 'response' elements, and that it uses 'para role="shortdesc"'.

So now, the only differences between the generated version of the documentation and the hand-written one are:

* the 'title' attribute of the 'wadl:doc' element. Not sure about what should be done here.
* the short descriptions of methods: Mehdi, do you think we could fix that in Ceilometer ?
* the ids of the methods: I think we cannot generate them, so I should probably make the doc generator ask the user to type in the ids. Obviously, it could write them to a cache and reuse these for the next compilation.


WDYT ?'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-11 19:17:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-11 19:17:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-noop http://logs.openstack.org/92/45592/10/check/gate-noop/7088f89 : SUCCESS in 0s
'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-11 19:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Removed white space from WADL.

As for the questions: 

    the 'title' attribute of the 'wadl:doc' element. Not sure about what should be done here.

-> If you create user-friendly method IDs, you could parse those to create the titles. For example, if the method name is "addSamples," break the phrase at the camel-cased "Samples" and make the title="Add Samples"

    the short descriptions of methods: Mehdi, do you think we could fix that in Ceilometer ?
    the ids of the methods: I think we cannot generate them, so I should probably make the doc generator ask the user to type in the ids. Obviously, it could write them to a cache and reuse these for the next compilation.

-> If you ask the user for these IDs, couldn't you just ask them for the method title, (like "Add Samples") and then create the ID for them -> AddSamples?'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-14 12:35:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

So, about the ids, I was able to generate the following ones, which I think are good:

listAlarms, createAlarm, listMeters, showMeter, createMeter, showMeterStatistics, listResources, showResource. I'll try and generate the titles from that, should be fine.

I noticed you wrapped the lines. I think I'll have to do that (manually). What's the maximum length of a line in api-site ?

Do you mind if we mark this as WIP, as long as the doc generator lacks some features ?"}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-14 16:20:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Do you want this to be part of the Havana release? We release the docs this week 10/17 - so we should push it through by then, right? 

As for line wraps, hmmm - sorry about that. I can fix that.'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-14 16:23:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I don't see where the line wraps are - point me to the file!"}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-14 16:46:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

The attributes of the "application" element are not on the same line, while they are in my generated output. Same goes for some text inside the "para" elements. I guess I could fix that by using the tidylib in my generator.

I'd love to remove the examples before pushing: they were just here for debugging purposes and we do not have many of them in Ceiloemter, so we'll add them later.'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-10-15 13:37:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Cyril, 

Whatever works! Remove the examples, fix the line wraps - 

thanks.'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-10-15 18:05:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-15 18:05:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

OK, how does this look ? The ids are reasonably human-readable, there are "title" attributes, and it's 100% generated.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-15 19:03:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: No score

commit_message:
Fixing restart tests

* Remove rax specific tests
* Fix delete test grouping
* Fix the mess up mysql logic
* Fix ovz command if CONF.use_local_ovz
* Fix logic in Checker that was masking errors in tests

Fixes: Bug #1204233

'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-09-24 01:31:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

still not ready for Icehouse changes :)

That withstanding,  personally I don't like proliferating config options, why do we need to have a duplicate config entry for every driver?  Why can't they just share the base NFS config options?  I don't see any value in this approach and in fact would like to see things go the complete opposite direction. 

In addition, just a heads up, you'll need better commit messages, and perhaps a BP or bug to associate with the commit in the future."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-01 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-01 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 2401, 'date': '2013-10-01 19:59:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Restored'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-10-04 15:55:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2013-10-08 14:56:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2013-10-08 16:13:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2013-10-14 05:06:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Based on the commit message, it's not clear what's supposed to happen with the nfs_oversub_ratio option for existing deployments using it. Deployments using other nfs drivers like netapp and gluster don't have their driver oversub_ratio option set. This also seems limited in cases where you have multiple nfs backends of the same driver. Do you just set the config value for all netapp nfs backends Cinder is managing? Tests need to be updated. This change needs more discussion before moving forward."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2013-10-14 17:34:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The basic idea here may make sense, but more work is needed:
- defining the options in other drivers like glusterfs_oversub_ratio (and maybe similar for NetApp, Nexenta, etc.)
- Currently only the NFS driver has code to make use of these options even if they are defined, so just the above doesn't get too far.

Maybe rather than using driver_prefix for x_oversub_ratio, we should just rename it to remotefs_oversub_ratio?  I'm not sure it's worth defining it in each driver when it means the same thing for each driver and can be set per-backend anyway as a more general option.

Worth some discussion, I think.  Maybe at least post a bug about this?"}, {'account_id': 2401, 'date': '2013-10-15 18:34:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Use driver_prefix in NfsDriver

Use driver_prefix in NfsDriver methods to give a chance for others
volume drivers, that inherit NfsDriver use their custom options.

Change-Id: Ic4a8d550856c14ae8ef0b08125098bb140a4ec09

commit_message:
The V2 Api should delete a non existent image

Glance V2 api initiates the deletion of an image that
got deleted during upload. This ensures that there
are no orphaned chunks of the image left behind

Fixes bug #1226013

Change-Id: I4cf5c49d2a6d2157a38467d9f7bcb20c4562b642

commit_message:
not install DHCP agent on compute node by default

From the quantum document, when there are 3 types
nodes: controller node, network node, and compute
node, it's always supposed that the network node
has OpenStack Networking L2 agent, DHCP agent and
L3 agent, and the compute node has OpenStack Networking
L2 agent and the OpenStack Compute services. There
is not the DHCP agent on the compute node.But the
current recipes always installs the DHCP agent on
the compute node by default. So remove the dhcp_agent
from the network plugins list, and the network_spec.rb
also is modified.

Closes-Bug: #1233009
Change-Id: I936a55ab055ee16b203df8479f18f3ea46a9870e

commit_message:
Make the request object API aware

The patch makes the Request object aware of the API but not dependent on
it. This gives to the Request object - and to the each transport
implementation - more information about what the current operation is
suppose to do, what params it accepts and what methods it can handle.

For example, a transport could use the API info to build the final URL
based on the ref specified there.

Partially-Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: I4ab1e2815807327706390aad4223c665a0ebeeda

commit_message:
Pass errors from *_format.parse() to the caller

This gives the user a nice helpful error message, something like:

ERROR: Template not in valid format: while parsing a block mapping
  in "<unicode string>", line 2, column 3:
      KeyName:
      ^


Change-Id: I1c0aaa955981eec264e1ff3cc66ad15adc771e72
Closes-bug: #1226106

commit_message:
Fix cleanup for testsets

Logic that introduces cleaning up actions after manual stop of testset
has been fixed. For smoke testset cleanup_path was added to
__profile__. cleanup function from cleanup.py has been modified so that
it now properly treats situations when different additional components
is not installed. To NoseDriver's method _clean_up was added
functionality that retrieves deployment tags for current cluster and
passes it to cleanup function which in turn perform proper cleaning
actions.

Change-Id: Ib7bd3c37d8b4cf57d1608f9ab3bb44f3b046e582

commit_message:
Replace using tests.utils part3

It is the last step to replace using tests.utils with
stack.common.test.
In this patch database tests is changed for using
openstack.common.test and added needed fixtures in test classes.

Blueprint: common-unit-tests
Change-Id: I9b360f9a8dc72bc3fb697e571555775bde10ef61

commit_message:
Wait for heat-admin to be configured on undercloud

cloud-init configures the heat-admin user after ssh comes up, if things
happen fast enough when init-keystone tries to ssh to the undercloud it
may stall while ssh waits for a password to be entered. We need to wait
for the ssh key to be in place.

Change-Id: I87edb55a38f2a3e21e1653e57e9849e971ba02c8

commit_message:
Remove deprecated NOVA_RAX_AUTH

NOVA_RAX_AUTH has been deprecated in favor of a generic pluggable auth,
which in this case rackspace users can set OS_AUTH_SYSTEM=rackspace

Fixes bug 966329

Change-Id: Ie55fc36a0ac1cba61efa8bdd2f20809530d3365f

commit_message:
add a simple run_tests.sh to use bash8

this gives a simple way to run against all the files that we'd
want to check with bash8. Currently clocking in at 300+ errors
(no false pos so far that I see).

commit_message:
Delete failed rabbit tests for 3.2

rabbit tests failed for 3.2. To make it pass
we need enabled rabbit management extention on each node
It will be done after 3.4 so delete failed tests for now

commit_message:
Avoid suppressing underlying error when deploy.loadapp fails

Raise log level at the first load attempt. If there is a
fundamental problem with the environment, a Lookup error
is not helpful in troubleshooting the problem further.

Fix bug 1210236

Change-Id: I55aa11a0e5a37dbef3f0c1b55aa4c9c11bbf55d9

commit_message:
Allow adding arguments to disk-image-create

This will allow us to set things like --offline or add elements like
pypi and others that are specific to our build environment.

Change-Id: I208ac2c316cf76fe928062d8a1c98a02aa1dff1c

commit_message:
Test for error in setUpClass

New test environment (new fixture data in nailgun_mimic.py, new fake
test for produce given error was added to dummy_tests, new test in
functional tests to test errorness behaviour) was added.

Fix bug with updating tests status after unhandled exception in
setUpClass of test case.

Method _add_message of StoragePlugin class from nose_storage_plugin.py
has been modified so that it now updates tests for ContextSuite with
error properly. New util function get_tests_ids_to_update was added to
nose_utils.py. This function performs recursive searching of tests in
ContextSuite object. Such functionality takes is needed in orded to
avoid problems that may occur when uhandled exception is raised in
setUpClass method of TestCase. Functional tests for new behaviour have
been created. Some non-major fixes and refactoring of different chunks
were added.

Change-Id: I5ef9cd7a139425ae38ac54a396301b7d0763b4d2

[{'created': '2013-10-12 21:26:43.000000000', 'message': 'Reduce the "minimal" set of required diagnostics

Change If631472081d16fe8c0b37575eb157a7b13d6fba4 introduced new restrictions
on the diagnostics API which are not valid with XenAPI and causes it to fail
tempest tests.

I haven't found documentation which describes the minimum set of diagnostics
so therefore I assume we can safely reduce this test to ensure a truly minimal
set

Closes bug: 1239209

Change-Id: I3e643d8e7a63b7dc42a912fab09ffc4222d463db
'}, {'created': '2013-10-15 11:57:20.000000000', 'message': 'Skip get_server_diagnostics test until bug 1240043 is fixed

commit_message:
Skip get_server_diagnostics test until bug 1240043 is fixed

Change If631472081d16fe8c0b37575eb157a7b13d6fba4 introduced new restrictions
on the diagnostics API which are not valid with XenAPI and causes it to fail
tempest tests.

Bug 1240043 has been raised to define a hypervisor-agnostic API which can be
tested and maintained

Closes bug: 1239209

Change-Id: I3e643d8e7a63b7dc42a912fab09ffc4222d463db

commit_message:
Test rediscovering for redeployed cluster fix

In models.py file descriprion of new entity called ClusterState was
added. This new entity stores info about current cluster state (its
deployment tags). Function discovery_check has been modified: logic that
controlls rediscovering of tests for redeployed cluster has been
changed. It now is based on data from ClusterState. Unit tests have been
fixed in orded to support new logic. New initial alembic migration has
been created (cluster_state entity is included).

Rediscovering logic has been fixed.

Change-Id: I61bf4d56a097a49413c494adee5587cfad83949c

This is of course completely fine, and the content is good.

Add KVM config info to the Install Guide

Add KVM config info from Config Reference
Update Enabling KVM in the native file
Update the references to QEMU and Xen
Create Enabling KVM section and use it from both Config
Reference and Install Guide
Add reference to amd and intel subsections

Closes-Bug: #1238256
Author: Nermina Miller

commit_message:
Make aggregate methods use new-world objects

This makes the add_aggregate_host() and remove_aggregate_host()
methods on compute manager use new-world objects. It introduces
a new compatibility decorator since object_compat() is specifically
tailored to instance methods, which makes sharing it really
complex and ugly.

Note that we still convert the aggregates back to primitive form
before passing to the drivers, which will be removed once we teach
the drivers to use/take aggregate objects directly (coming next).

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I241876b6b2ebdb2313e472c043fcc73c6ddd0e1a

commit_message:
Add a create_router utility function

Similary to other neutron resources, add a utility function for
creating a logical router in tempest.api.network.base.BaseNetworkClient

Also, adapt test_floating_ips to use this function

Change-Id: I36f60028f75f7d4b2ed814a965431d2d4138cfbd
Partial-Bug: #1228091

commit_message:
Restores passing additional parameters to nosetest

Parameters after -- are only passed to testr and not to nosetest.
The patch restores the old behaviour.

Change-Id: Ia25b0c071f7292a5ddf34f057b19d03f879dc0af

commit_message:
remove tearDownClass in test_quotas.py

There is no need for the functionality of the tearDownClass in the
api/compute/admin/test_quotas.py, becase it's already included in the base
class. So it should be removed.

Change-Id: Ic0e145952cc143d65291258fc9567807ca051596
closes-bug: #1239722

commit_message:
python3: Make iteritems py3k compat

Use six.iteritems to replace dictionary.iteritems() on python2 or
dictionary.items() on python3.

Change-Id: I972f065414e22d287bd7e00ab2c6e754f17afb75
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

messages:
[{'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:32:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I investigated the reported bug. IMO the root cause is that makemessages script from Django (./manage.py makemessages or ./run_tests.sh --makemessages) does not extract I18N strings from *.csv template files.

How did you generate these files in this patch? What commandline?

Simply updating PO files does not solve the problem. We need to update the script itself. This is the reason of -1."}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:36:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually, I use following cmd

../manage.py  makemessages -a --settings=openstack_dashboard.settings --extension html,txt,csv

But where is the script you mentioned? And we should update that files.'}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2013-10-14 13:37:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You can get the detail from

commit_message:
don't doubly escape html files

we want to process console.html files for timestamp links, however
these files are already escaped by jenkins to be valid html, so
our previous assumption that we should always escape lines is
invalid.

based on the filename, don't doubly escape the lines in the file.
Added unit tests to ensure we had expected console.html output
after running it through the filter.

Change-Id: I3a0e6bca782b134bed9f385be056befd3a2f30c7

commit_message:
Add third element to RPC versions for backports

This makes the RPC version support three elements, adding a "revision"
in addition to the major and minor version. The revision would always
be zero for the master branch of a service, but could be incremented
for stable versions. This provides us some room to backport fixes
that affect RPC versions in such a way that would avoid breaking
the version lineage for systems running stable versions that may
some day be involved in a rolling upgrade to a version from master.

I didn't find any tests for version_is_compatible(), so I added
some for existing version scenarios, as well as new ones with
revisions. They also serve to validate that this doesn't break
anything for code using two-element versions (the expectation is that
two-element versions will still be used everywhere until a third
is needed).

Porting chages from Change-Id I239c17a3e305f572493498c4b96ee3c7514c5881
to oslo-incubator

commit_message:
Handle the case no SimpleTenantUsage Nova extension

When the SimpleTenantUsage Nova extension is not enabled,
panels that include usages produce an error and
the usage table is useless.

Three panels use the SimpleTenantUsage extension:
- openstack_dashboard.dashboards.admin.overview
- openstack_dashboard.dashboards.admin.projects
- openstack_dashboard.dashboards.project.overview

This fix avoids errors and does not show the usage
table in such a case.

A context variable 'simple_tenant_usage_enabled' is now
available in templates rendered by usage.UsageView subclasses.

Unit tests now mock nova 'extension_supported' API.

Change-Id: Ib306846bf6c947572ba0e7c773125d03b3dbf68b
Closes-Bug: #1211470

[{'created': '2013-10-15 06:26:55.000000000', 'message': 'align the order of parameters for urlencode()

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ
across Python runs.

In the test case, the fixed expecting string will not match the test
result, it is relying on the dict order.

This change transforms the input dict to a sequence of two-element list,
with fixed order, and update the related expecitng string / fixture
in test cases.

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

commit_message:
align the order of parameters for urlencode()

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ
across Python runs.

In the test case, the fixed expecting string will not match the test
result, it is relying on the dict order.

This change transforms the input dict to a sequence of two-element list,
with fixed order, and update the related expecitng string / fixture
in test cases.

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: I6dccde9e584be8335a6375f5fbad5c5cbd7b9b6d

commit_message:
Add the option to minimize ovs l2 polling

This change adds the ability to monitor the local ovsdb for
interface changes so that the l2 agent can avoid unnecessary
polling.  Minimal changes are made to the agent so the risk
of breakage should be low.  Future efforts to make the agent
entirely event-based may be able to use OvsdbMonitor as a
starting point.

By default polling minimization is not done, and can only be
enabled by setting 'minimize_polling = True' in the ovs
section of the l2 agent's config file.

Closes-Bug: #1177973

Change-Id: I26c035b48a74df2148696869c5a9affae5ab3d27

commit_message:
Improve ovs_lib bridge management

Add the ability to add and remove bridges, check for bridge
existence, and lookup the bridge associated with a port.

This change is in support of functional testing for an ovsdb
monitor.

Partial-Bug: #1177973

Change-Id: I419923d8d77983997cd347fcf063b0bc367c0bbc

commit_message:
Add assertNotEquals check to H602

There are some projects that mix assertNotEqual and assertNotEquals
in their testscripts. According to Python 3 source code, assertNotEquals
is also deprecated. This patch adds a check for assertNotEquals in H602 since
it already handles assertEquals and has not been released yet.

Lib/unittest/case.py:
    failIfEqual = assertNotEquals = _deprecate(assertNotEqual)

Change-Id: I087bd4b23cb2daa59a1df32926ddcc5cc2052f5c

So I'm not opposed to this per say, but we've seen some issues in the past with server reuse causing random crashes in the gate. (which are probably bugs that needed to be sorted anyway so that's not a bad thing) I'm just curious if there is a reason using less vms here is needed? Are we running out of resources when running the tests?

Otherwise I'm inclined to say lets just leave this alone for now. Although I'd be fine with breaking the rebuild_servers() call to the base server test. Hi Matthew,

 > So I'm not opposed to this per say, but we've seen some issues
 > in the past with server reuse causing random crashes in the gate.
 > (which are probably bugs that needed to be sorted anyway so that's not a bad thing)

I also think this reusing mechanism is nice to find latent bugs, I found the one of Nova shelve/unshelve APIs yesterday with this mechanism.
We are trying to fix it now.

 > Are we running out of resources when running the tests?

Now many negative tests are queued in Gerrit, and the tests would increase.
So this will be able to avoid running out of resources in the future.

Also by reducing vm creations, the running time of Tempest can shrink, I guess."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-10-13 04:31:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Reduce vm creations in negative tests

In test_server_actions.py, there is a feature that the same server is
used with all test cases. The feature have reduced vm creations.
This patch adds the same feature to negative tests.

Change-Id: I286082e3a8d35bc57049741bedb8026021b653bd

commit_message:
Adds common image utils

This is the first step to merge the code in nova/virt/images.py
and cinder/image/image_utils.py.

This patch pulls up the QemuImgInfo class which is common
in the two modules above.
The test script is based on nova/tests/virt/test_images.py with
an additional test_qemu_info_blank testcase.

Partially implements bp imageutils

Change-Id: Ia07739492776180e579b03920aa32b9215ce941d

commit_message:
Net probe fails with timeout on check_dhcp request with a lot of iface and vlans

Change-Id: I49610410eb414bea43e3cb3dc62b043bee9d5427
Solution: Provide interface to limit time waiting for response and times request is repeated

commit_message:
Refactoring of log preparation initial ubuntu progress bar
* small refactoring
* add support log progress for multiple OSes
* create separate file for exceptions
* fix indentations
* remove pending test

Tested by hand for centos/ubuntu in simple mode.
More tests will be in next patches.

Change-Id: Id3e0131819c33a96409578f05b3808765d6c0d08

commit_message:
Add log_handler to implement the publish_errors config option

This handler sends all error logs as rpc notifications.
Note: when using publish_errors you also need to set the
notification_driver option too.

Change-Id: I9ceb1fa92118161779b4b29e2cdc3b91f79ab733
Closes-bug: #1229246

commit_message:
Update oslo in ceilometer part2

Update oslo in ceilometer. It's the second step to update oslo for replace using
ceilometer.tests.base with openstack.common.test in the future.

SHA of last oslo's commit before adding in ceilometer: 8a3996a411ac23b19f13553798a8d3fc356ecf9f

Change-Id: I999b0ed30dcc449dc73d8ac5d86b8fe0b36ac877

commit_message:
Update oslo in ceilometer part1

Update oslo in ceilometer. It's the first step to update oslo for replace using
ceilometer.tests.base with openstack.common.test in the future.

SHA of last oslo's commit before adding in ceilometer: 8a3996a411ac23b19f13553798a8d3fc356ecf9f

Change-Id: I0148a874f9807698af976a714d0c86bba6f68284

commit_message:
Replace unicode() with six.u()

six.u(text)
A fake unicode literal. text should always be a normal string literal.
In Python 2, u() returns unicode, and in Python 3, a string.

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: I02849e540c1fbb1f8b02bcbfa4d9be4f60279926

Use "from __future__ import print_function"
docs.python.org/3/howto/pyporting.html#from-future-import-print-function

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: I92fc07257851795a9972c8273d3278c8679d6628

commit_message:
Fix module importing issues for Python 3

Copy py3kcompat from oslo for urlparse
Substitute StringIO / httplib with six

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: Ic8da2ca53b4217ef13f15be094437f1f4e643001

commit_message:
Import six.StringIO

six.StringIO
This is an fake file object for textual data. It is an alias for
StringIO.StringIO in Python 2 and io.StringIO in Python 3.

Partial Implement: blueprint py33-support

Change-Id: I76c05041565614241eea7b7595e4503c88211ee8

commit_message:
Change netaddress types to raw

If the value is left as a blank string (the default in a devtest run
on overcloud), the call to os-config-applier errors as '' doesn't
match the netaddress type. This in turn causes os-collect-config to
fail.

Change-Id: Id8a48f1171f484d9e52ebed481d1fa6dd47f8777

It print the exception of the samples publishing failure instead of

commit_message:
Don't publish samples if resource_id in missing

In swift API, the user can call uri without the resource_id.
This patch skip the samples publishing instead of raising the
exception:

Traceback (most recent call last):
File "ceilometer/objectstore/swift_middleware.py", line 109, in iter_response
    bytes_sent)
File "ceilometer/objectstore/swift_middleware.py", line 160, in publish_sample
    resource_id=account.partition('AUTH_')[2],
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'partition'

It print the exception of the samples publishing failure instead of
raising a exception to never break the swift API.

Fixes bug #1223259

Change-Id: I5d90fa620c8f8ea82e86524b9703049257ca0345
(cherry picked from commit e52e5070b3e0fb8c71e806eda036631e25628800)

commit_message:
Fix get_resources timestamp ordering for SQLAlchemy

This patch ports over the ResourceTestOrdering tests from
Ceilometer Master (Havana-3 RC-1) and applies them to the
SQLAlchemy driver for stable/grizzly along with a fix.
Partial cherry-pick from
change ID Ib09e21cbc7bbd45a6ecc321403e9947df837e14b.

Change-Id: If2d4299d17afc2d0d29433fcdccdfd5d85498cef
Partial-Bug: #1229395

commit_message:
Make LaunchConfiguration resources mergeable

This can be very useful for merging of Metadata to be used
by optional services (e. g. to add services like tuskar to
undercloud on demand).

Change-Id: Ifc4016d6e994064c0772c12e668e98bf055fada9

Compute API is_volume_backed_instance used to rely on matching the
device name to the root_device_name field of the instance which had
several problems and edge cases.

Now that we have moved to the new BDM format that has the boot_index
and destination_type field for each block device - it is pretty
staightforward to implement.

Change-Id: Ia2c235f8bce577ed4ac6a480a4a051d159a5fad7
blueprint: clean-up-legacy-block-device-mapping
'}]
commit_message:
Move is_volume_backed_instance to new style BDM

Compute API is_volume_backed_instance used to rely on matching the
device name to the root_device_name field of the instance which had
several problems and edge cases.

Now that we have moved to the new BDM format that has the boot_index
and destination_type field for each block device - it is pretty
staightforward to implement.

Change-Id: Ia2c235f8bce577ed4ac6a480a4a051d159a5fad7
blueprint: clean-up-legacy-block-device-mapping

idiom and we use it in several places in our code base. This patch

commit_message:
Add a get_root_bdm utility function

Getting the root block device out of a list of block devices is a common
idiom and we use it in several places in our code base. This patch
factors it out in a handy utilty method and adds tests for it.

Change-Id: I4a2cb3c689fed9fbc0bc51ddba095e1269cacb2d
blueprint: clean-up-legacy-block-device-mapping

I might argue that the fix belongs to Nova, where you can catch and handler the 404 correctly."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-10-05 08:24:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Armando.
It is mainly a nova side issue. What should nova behave when nova.conf security_group_driver is neutron and neutron security group is not enabled/supported? Not all neutron plugin does not support security group extension.

There is another discussion point to be considered in Neutron side.

In my understanding, setting NoopFirewallDriver means that neutron with agent-based plugin does not provide a security group feature. It only comes from the historical reason. The default value of firewall_driver in neutron is NoopFirewallDriver and it is used when Nova security group implementation with Neutron. it is a historical reason to avoid confusions (e.g., in a case where neutron security group is enabled and it actually does nothing). Now it becomes common that neutron security group is enabled when neutron is used, so it may be a good chance to discuss whether security group extension should be enabled even when NoopFirewallDriver is used.

It is not a client issue."}, {'account_id': 7823, 'date': '2013-10-09 07:28:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Great thanks to Armando and Akihiro,
  First I am sorry to response so late.
  
  I have understood the point that "Not all neutron plugin does not support security group extension". 
  while still confused with that "it is a historical reason to avoid confusions 
(e.g., in a case where neutron security group is enabled and it actually does nothing)"
  Does set NoopFirewallDriver in neutron equal to "neutron security group is enabled and it actually does nothing" 
when security_group_api = neutron in nova?
  What are the confusions specified? Any more suggestions and instructions are welcomed.

  Thank you very much.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-10-15 04:45:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

First, I would like to say it should be handled in nova side (perhaps neutron security group driver). Several projects use neutronclient and the basic layer should keep its behavior backward compatible. Catching an exception in v2.0/client.py hides an exception and caller cannot distinguish an empty list and an exception (security group extension is not supported). This is the main reason of -1.

The other reason is to keep consistency throughout the neutron client library. I don't think it is a good idea that only security group call has a different behavior compared to other API calls in the client library.


Regarding historical reason part, I need to apologize the description is not sufficient. When quantum security group was implemented, someone used nova security group and others used quantum security group. We need to switch firewall_driver between Noop and Hybrid to enabled/disable quantum security group, and the only way to know quantum security group really works is to check the config file. We thought it was better that we have more obvious way to know whether quantum security group is really enabled. The behavior of NoopDriver is exactly same as the behavior without quantum security group except API behavior, so I made the change to disable security group extension when NoopDriver is used. This is the background reason.

IMO now it is common to enable neutron security group when neutron is used, so it may be a good chance whether security group extension should be enabled even when NoopDriver is used (while it brings nothing actually)."}, {'account_id': 7823, 'date': '2013-10-15 08:26:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thank Akihiro for the very detailed background information, it's pretty clear to me.

I agree with you that this bug should be fixed in the nova module.

It's appreciated for your wonderful comments : )"}, {'account_id': 7823, 'date': '2013-10-15 08:26:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Rebased'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-15 08:26:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Support Nova functions if using NoopFirewallDriver in Neutron

The command nova list is not working if setting NoopFirewallDriver
as firewall in Neutron, since the extension of security groups won't
be loaded by Neutron, which leads an exception raised by neutronclient.

    * Catch the neutronclient exception in function list_security_groups()
    * Add unit test

Closes-Bug #1232965

Change-Id: I2ebb77734345930a53f00a3873c43f013c94af9b

commit_message:
Remove obsolete redhat-eventlet.patch

See I62ce43a330d7ae94eda4c7498782a655e63747fa for the gorey details on
why this exists.

As of this fix:

  https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/pull/34

which was released in eventlet 0.13, we no longer need the patch.

This has now been removed from oslo-incubator, so this is really just
syncing that removal.

Change-Id: I84267f3c6726cb2e750f615e107c48b12c6ed353

please see comments inline"}, {'account_id': 7629, 'date': '2013-08-01 22:15:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

I'm going to pull this code and run some functional tests on it Monday/Tuesday and report back here."}, {'account_id': 7629, 'date': '2013-08-07 03:23:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

More notes. A short book on why caching in datastores can be a good thing, why it can be a bad thing, and how vCenter interacts with datastores and ESXi hosts. The topic is deep as the combination of services can interact in multiple ways. Ultimately that means we need to provide a driver that is flexible and will allow spot-tuning for performance or storage based on the particular clouds' needs.

I've run out of time today and plan on working with this patch some more tomorrow.

Questions: 

* how do you specify when you want an ephemeral disk and when you don't?
* how do you specify that you want the ephemeral disk to be linked-clone?
* how do you specify you want the ephemeral disk to be linked-clone and the root disk to be full-clone?"}, {'account_id': 1313, 'date': '2013-08-07 14:30:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (2 inline comments)

Shawn,

how do you specify when you want an ephemeral disk and when you don't?

the ephemeral disk is specified in instance flavors, the cloud admin can create customed flavors.


how do you specify that you want the ephemeral disk to be linked-clone?

I don't see any value to make ephemeral disk to be linked-clone, can you please explain some usecases or benefits to do this?
 
how do you specify you want the ephemeral disk to be linked-clone and the root disk to be full-clone?

commit_message:
Enhance VMware instance disk usage

Add instance image cache mechanism, when use_linked_clone is enabled,
images downloaded from Glance will be extend to the specified flavor
size and store in image base directory as cache. The instance root disk
will use the cached image files as link clone. If use_linked_clone is
disabled, we will copy the full image from cache to instance directory.

This patch also adds support for ephemeral disk.

Implement blueprint improve-vmware-disk-usage

Change-Id: I62e2967e1ef2e85ec653d75d3b3a90aeb9331412

commit_message:
Updating address pairs with xml doesn't work

Below command can't work because list element
"allowed_address_pairs" hasn't been updated
into the varaiable "attr.PLURALS"
"neutron port-update <port-uuid> \
--allowed-address-pairs list=true type=dict \
ip_address=10.0.0.1 --request-format xml"

Change-Id: I0d7dcca5f4848bc968f5c86fbeb46569c70c8fcd
Closes-Bug: #1229954

commit_message:
Rename cli tests from compute to nova

All other CLI tests use the codenames (neutron, keystone, etc).  In
order to make things uniform do the same for nova (compute).

Change-Id: I2f299e1078924643e6e556275892775228176e11

add a try/finally to ensure the LOG.debug is printed
properly. Currently the debug message is never executed

Apply six for metaclass

__metaclass__ cannot be used in python3.six be used in general
for python 3 compatibility.

Porting Change-Id I9fc7a59df3af29b4cc1287c40fa4e883d994a961
from oslo-incubator
